<div class='top-bar'><h1 class='left3'>Documentation</h1><input class='right3' id='searchbox' type='search' placeholder='Search text' value=''/><div class='middle3'><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/' target='_blank'><img src='codeskulptor.png' alt='CodeSkulptor' width='129' height='30'/></a></div><div class='top-bar-end'></div></div> <div id="tabs" class="hideload">
<ul><li><a href='#tabs-Python' title='The core Python language syntax, as supported by CodeSkulptor'>Python Syntax</a></li><li><a href='#tabs-Types' title='The core Python types and operations, as supported by CodeSkulptor'>Types &amp; Operations</a></li><li><a href='#tabs-StdModules' title='The standard Python library, as supported by CodeSkulptor'>Standard Modules</a></li><li><a href='#tabs-Graphics' title='CodeSkulptor-specific graphics modules'>Graphics Modules</a></li><li><a href='#tabs-Other' title='Other CodeSkulptor-specific modules'>Other Modules</a></li><li><a href='#tabs-CS' title='How to use CodeSkulptor'>CodeSkulptor</a></li><li><a class='hide searchtab' href='#tabs-Search' title='Search this documentation'>Search</a></li></ul>
<div id="tabs-Python">
<p>
<a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/' target='_blank'>CodeSkulptor</a> is a browser-based Python interpreter,
as featured in the online course
<a href='https://www.coursera.org/course/interactivepython' target='_blank'>&ldquo;An Introduction to Interactive Programming in Python&rdquo;</a>.
It implements a subset of
<a href='http://docs.python.org/2/' target='_blank'>Python&nbsp;2</a>,
plus the addition of three graphical libraries,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='tabs-Graphics'>SimpleGui, SimpleMap, and SimplePlot</a>.
</p>
<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='types'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Types</span></a></h3> <div>
<dt>Types:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Numbers'>Integers</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Numbers'>Floating-point numbers</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Booleans'>Booleans</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Strings'>strings</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Tuples'>tuples</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lists'>lists</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Dictionaries'>dictionaries</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='DefaultDictionaries'>default dictionaries</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Counters'>counters</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Sets'>sets</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='NoneType'>the null object</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Functions'>functions</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Generators'>generators</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Enumerations'>enumerations</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Files'>file objects</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='RE'>match objects</a></li></ul></dd>
<p>
It does not support
NotImplemented,
Ellipsis,
complex numbers,
Unicode strings,
bytearrays,
frozensets,
exceptions,
xrange objects, or
memory view objects.
In particular, when CodeSkulptor raises a Python error,
it simply prints an error message, rather than returning
an exception value.
</p>
<p>
<dfn>Mutable</dfn> types are those that have operations that
mutate or update part of the value.
Other types are <dfn>immutable</dfn>.
Numbers, Booleans, strings, tuples, and functions are
immutable, while all other types are mutable.
</p>
</div> <!-- Closes Types -->

<h3 id='values-objects'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Values &amp; Objects</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
In Python, all values are objects, and objects can have
<dfn>attributes</dfn>. Attributes that are functions
are known as
<a href='http://docs.python.org/2/library/stdtypes.html#methods' target='_blank'><dfn>methods</dfn></a>.
An object is an instance of a <dfn>class</dfn>.
Some classes are built-in, like lists and sets,
but others can be user-defined.
</p>

<p>
For user-defined classes,
Codeskulptor supports only &ldquo;classic&rdquo;
or &ldquo;old-style&rdquo; classes, not &ldquo;new-style&rdquo;
classes. It supports instance methods, but not
the less commonly used class methods and static methods.
</p>

<p>
<dfn>Hashable</dfn> values are any for which the Python
implementation defines a way to convert it into an integer
(its <dfn>hash value</dfn>).
In practice, a value is hashable if it is immutable.
CodeSkulptor does not support the standard
<code>__hash__()</code> method.
</dd>
</div> <!-- Closes Values and Operations -->

<h3 id='expressions'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Expressions</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
CodeSkulptor supports all forms of Python
<a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/expressions.html' target='_blank'>expressions</a>,
except dictionary and set comprehensions.
</p>

<dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_variables-names.py' target='_blank'>Variables &amp; Naming</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_functions-scope.py' target='_blank'>Scope</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2a_local_vs_global-example.py' target='_blank'>Local vs. Global Variables</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_variables-operations.py' target='_blank'>Operations</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_variables-formulas.py' target='_blank'>Formulas</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_functions-uses.py' target='_blank'>Function Uses/Calls</a></li></ul></dd>
<p>
See the other sections of this documentation for details on
which types, operations, functions, and methods are supported.
</p>
</div> <!-- Closes Expressions -->

<h3 id='simple-statements'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Simple Statements</span></a></h3> <div>
<dt>Simple Statements:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#assignment-statements' target='_blank'>assignments</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-assert-statement' target='_blank'><code>assert</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-break-statement' target='_blank'><code>break</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-continue-statement' target='_blank'><code>continue</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-del-statement' target='_blank'><code>del</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-global-statement' target='_blank'><code>global</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-import-statement' target='_blank'><code>import</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-pass-statement' target='_blank'><code>pass</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-print-statement' target='_blank'><code>print</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-return-statement' target='_blank'><code>return</code></a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-yield-statement' target='_blank'><code>yield</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_codeskulptor-prints_strings_comments.py' target='_blank'>Comments (<code>#</code>) &amp; <code>print</code></a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_variables-assignment.py' target='_blank'>Assignment (<code>=</code>)</a></li></ul></dd>
<p>
Simple statements are those which cannot contain other
statements. I.e., they are not compound.
</p>

<p>
The only unsupported simple statements are
<code>exec</code>,
<code>raise</code>.
</p>

</div> <!-- Closes Simple Statements -->

<h3 id='compound-statements'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Compound Statements</span></a></h3> <div>
<dt>Compound Statements:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/compound_stmts.html#the-if-statement' target='_blank'>conditionals (<code>if</code>)</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/compound_stmts.html#the-for-statement' target='_blank'><code>for</code>-loops</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/compound_stmts.html#the-while-statement' target='_blank'><code>while</code>-loops</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/compound_stmts.html#defining-functions' target='_blank'>function definitions</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2.7/reference/compound_stmts.html#class-definitions' target='_blank'>class definitions</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_conditionals-if-elif-else.py' target='_blank'>Conditionals (<code>if</code>-<code>elif</code>-<code>else</code>)</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_conditionals-examples.py' target='_blank'>Functions with Conditionals</a></li></ul></dd>
<p>
Compound statements are those that can be built from smaller
statements.
</p>

<p>
CodeSkulptor does not support
<code>try-except</code> statements,
<code>with</code> statements,
&ldquo;new-style&rdquo; class definitions.
(Note: <code>try-except</code> is partially implemented,
but its use is not currently recommended.)
</p>
</div> <!-- Closes Compound Statements -->

<h3 id='style'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Python Code Style</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Good code and documentation style makes programs easier
to read and debug.
Using a style that is consistent with other programmers
further helps others to read your code.
</p>

<p>
<a href='http://docs.python-guide.org/en/latest/writing/style/' target='_blank'>The Python Guide on Code Style</a> provides a good summary with examples.
For a more details, see the official Python style guides for
<a href='http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/' target='_blank'>code</a> (&ldquo;PEP 8&rdquo;) and
<a href='http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0257/' target='_blank'>docstrings</a> (&ldquo;PEP 257&rdquo;).
</p>
</div> <!-- Closes Python Code Style -->
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in tabs-Python -->
</div> <!-- Closes tabs-Python -->

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='NoneType'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Null Object</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The single value <code>None</code> is known as the null object.
Its type is the NoneType.
It serves as a placeholder
return value for functions that would otherwise return nothing.
It is also used as an special argument value to some operations,
such as
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-filter'><code>filter()</code></a> and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-split'><code>a_str.split()</code></a>.
</p>
</div> <!-- Closes null object -->

class='internal' data-dest='Math'>Math Module</a> &mdash; Library of numeric operations</dd> </dl>
<p>
Integers have a limited number of digits, whereas
long integers can have an arbitrary number of digits.
Operations that normally produce an integer will instead
produce a long integer, if more digits are needed.
Operations on long integers are slower than on other numbers.
</p>

<p>
Floating-point numbers have a decimal point and a limited
number of digits. Arithmetic operations on floating-point
numbers can give somewhat inaccurate results because of
the limited precision.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Integers-Floats-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Integer &amp; Floating-point Constants</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12</pre></td><td><pre>12</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print -12.0</pre></td><td><pre>-12</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 0b1001</pre></td><td><pre>9</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 021</pre></td><td><pre>17</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print -021</pre></td><td><pre>-17</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 0x3A8</pre></td><td><pre>936</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12L</pre></td><td><pre>12</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890</pre></td><td><pre>12345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFL</pre></td><td><pre>340282366920938463463374607431768211455</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print +12.12345</pre></td><td><pre>12.12345</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print -12.12345</pre></td><td><pre>-12.12345</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 1.2e3</pre></td><td><pre>1200</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 1.2e-3</pre></td><td><pre>0.0012</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Integers can be given in any of four bases:
</p>
<ul>
<li>
Base ten (decimal &mdash; what people are most used to):
consists of a sequence of digits, not starting with 0
</li>
<li>
Base two (binary):
consists of 0b followed by 0's and 1's
</li>
<li>
Base eight (octal):
consists of a 0 followed by digits in the range 0 to 7
</li>
<li>
Base sixteen (hexadecimal):
consists of 0x followed by digits in the range 0 to 7
or letters in the range A to F (in upper or lower case)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
Integers can be preceded by a positive or negative sign.
Any integer followed by an <code>L</code> or whose absolute
value is greater than some minimum is consider a
long integer.
</p>

<p>
Floating-point numbers consist of a series of digits,
a decimal point, and another series of digits.
They can be preceded by an optional positive or
negative sign.
They can be followed by an optional exponent &mdash;
the letter <code>e</code>, an optional positive or
negative sign, and a series of digits.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='int'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Number, String, or Boolean into Number</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>int()</code>, <code>long()</code>,
<code>float()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>int(x)</code></dd><dd><code>long(x)</code></dd><dd><code>float(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print int()</pre></td><td><pre>0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print int('234')</pre></td><td><pre>234</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print int(1.6)</pre></td><td><pre>1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print int(False)</pre></td><td><pre>0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print long()</pre></td><td><pre>0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print long('234')</pre></td><td><pre>234</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print long(1.6)</pre></td><td><pre>1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print long(False)</pre></td><td><pre>0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float()</pre></td><td><pre>0.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float('3.89')</pre></td><td><pre>3.89</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float('inf')</pre></td><td><pre>inf</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float('-inf')</pre></td><td><pre>-inf</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float(3)</pre></td><td><pre>3.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print float(False)</pre></td><td><pre>0.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='round'><code>round()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds to nearest integer</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-trunc'><code>math.trunc()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds to zero (same <code>int()</code> and <code>long()</code> on integers)</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-ceil'><code>math.ceil()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds up</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-floor'><code>math.floor()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds down</dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a number, <code>int()</code> and <code>long()</code>
return the integer part of it, i.e.,
they round towards zero.
Given a Boolean, they return zero
(i.e., <code>0</code>, <code>0L</code>, or <code>0.0</code>)
for <code>False</code>, and one
(i.e., <code>1</code>, <code>1L</code>, or <code>1.0</code>)
for <code>True</code>.
Given a string containing a printed representation of
an integer, <code>int()</code> and <code>long()</code>
return that integer.
Similarly, given a string containing a printed
representation of a number, <code>float()</code>
returns that number. Special cases for <code>float()</code>
are the inputs <code>"inf"</code> and <code>"-inf"</code>,
representing positive and negative infinity, respectively.
Given any other
string, these raise a <code>ValueError</code>.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='plus'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Addition</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>+</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a + b</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 3 + 12</pre></td><td><pre>15</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns the sum of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code>.
Standard addition operation.
</p>

<p>
Addition and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>a += b</code>, which is equivalent to
<code>a = a + b</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='minus'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Subtraction &amp; Negation</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>-</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a - b</code></dd><dd><code>- a</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12 - 3</pre></td><td><pre>9</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a = 3
print -a</pre></td><td><pre>-3</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
With two arguments, returns the difference of
<code>a</code> and <code>b</code>.
Standard subtraction operation.
</p>

<p>
With one argument, return the negation of <code>a</code>.
Equivalent to <code>0 - a</code>.
</p>

<p>
Subtraction and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>a -= b</code>, which is equivalent to
<code>a = a - b</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='multiply'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Multiplication</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>*</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a * b</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 3 * 12</pre></td><td><pre>36</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns product of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code>.
Standard multiplication operation.
</p>

<p>
Multiplication and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>a *= b</code>, which is equivalent to
<code>a = a * b</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='divide'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Division</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>/</code>, <code>//</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a / b</code></dd><dd><code>a // b</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12 / 3</pre></td><td><pre>4</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 11 / 3</pre></td><td><pre>3</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 11 // 3</pre></td><td><pre>3</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 12.0 / 3.0</pre></td><td><pre>4.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 11.0 / 3.0</pre></td><td><pre>3.6666666666666665</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 11.0 // 3.0</pre></td><td><pre>3.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_arithmetic_expressions-division.py' target='_blank'>Division</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The standard division operation, <code>/</code>,
returns the quotient of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code>.
When both <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are integers,
then so is the result, i.e., the result is instead
the floor of the quotient.
</p>

<p>
The integer division operation, <code>//</code>,
returns the floor of the quotient of
<code>a</code> and <code>b</code>, i.e., the
integer part.
When both <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are integers,
then so is the result, otherwise the result is a
floating-point number with no value after the decimal.
</p>

<p>
Division and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>a /= b</code> and <code>a //= b</code>,
which are equivalent to <code>a = a / b</code> and
<code>a = a // b</code>, respectively.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='modulo'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Remainder (Modulo)</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>%</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>x % m</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 11 % 3</pre></td><td><pre>2</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_more_operations-modulus.py' target='_blank'>Modulus</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns the remainder of <code>x // m</code>.
</p>

<p>
Modulo and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>x %= m</code>, which is equivalent to
<code>x = x % m</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='exponent'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Exponentiation, <var>x</var><sup><var>y</var></sup></span><span class='accheadcode'><code>**</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>x ** y</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 3 ** 4</pre></td><td><pre>81</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='pow'><code>pow()</code></a> &mdash; Built-in exponentiation function</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-exponent'><code>math.pow()</code> and <code>math.exp()</code></a> &mdash; Similar exponentiation functions</dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns <code>x</code> to the power of <code>y</code>.
</p>

<p>
Exponentiation and assignment can be combined with the
shorthand <code>x **= y</code>, which is equivalent to
<code>x = x ** y</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='pow'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Exponentiation Remainder</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>pow()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>pow(x, y)</code></dd><dd><code>pow(x, y, m)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print pow(3, 4)</pre></td><td><pre>81</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print pow(3, 4, 2)</pre></td><td><pre>1</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='exponent'><code>**</code></a> &mdash; Built-in exponentiation operator</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-exponent'><code>math.pow()</code> and <code>math.exp()</code></a> &mdash; Similar exponentiation functions</dd> </dl>
<p>
Given a number <code>m</code>,
this returns the remainder of <code>x</code> to the power
of <code>y</code>, divided by <code>m</code>.
Given no <code>m</code>, this returns <code>x</code>
to the power of <code>y</code>, just like
<code>x ** y</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='abs'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Absolute Value, |<var>x</var>|</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>abs()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>abs(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print abs(3)</pre></td><td><pre>3</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print abs(-3.0)</pre></td><td><pre>3.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-fabs'><code>math.fabs()</code></a> &mdash; Always returns a floating-point number</dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns the absolute value of number <code>x</code>.
The result is of the same type as the input.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='round'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Round to Nearest</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>round()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>round(n)</code></dd><dd><code>round(n, i)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print round(12)</pre></td><td><pre>12.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print round(12.5)</pre></td><td><pre>13.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print round(-12.5)</pre></td><td><pre>-12.0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print round(123.4567, 2)</pre></td><td><pre>123.46</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print round(123.4567, -2)</pre></td><td><pre>100.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='int'><code>int()</code> and <code>long()</code></a> &mdash; Round to zero</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-trunc'><code>math.trunc()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds to zero</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-ceil'><code>math.ceil()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds up</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='math-floor'><code>math.floor()</code></a> &mdash; Rounds down</dd> </dl>
<p>
With one number argument, it returns the floating-point
number that represents the integer nearest <code>n</code>.
</p>
<p>
With two number arguments, it returns the floating-point
number that represents <code>n</code> rounded to the
nearest unit of 10<sup><code>i</code></sup>,
for integer <code>i</code>.
I.e., when <code>i</code> is positive, this is the
familiar idea of rounding to <code>i</code> places
after the decimal. However, <code>i</code> can be
zero or negative, as well.
</p>
<p>
In either case, a 5 digit is always rounded up.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='base'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Base Conversion</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>bin()</code>, <code>oct()</code>,
<code>hex()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>bin(x)</code></dd><dd><code>oct(x)</code></dd><dd><code>hex(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bin(9)</pre></td><td><pre>0b1001</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print oct(-17)</pre></td><td><pre>-021</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print hex(936)</pre></td><td><pre>0x3a8</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Given an integer, returns a string representing that
number in binary, octal, or hexadecimal, respectively.
The resulting string is in the same syntax as
Python integer constants.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='chr'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>ASCII Character</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>chr()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>chr(i)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print chr(97)</pre></td><td><pre>a</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns a string of one character whose
<a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII' target='_blank'>ASCII</a> code is the integer <code>i</code>.
This is the inverse of <code>ord()</code>.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='ord'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Character Code</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>ord()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>ord(x)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ord('a')</pre></td><td><pre>97</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Given a string of length one, returns an integer
representing the Unicode code point of the character
when the argument is a unicode object, or the value
of the byte when the argument is an 8-bit string.
This is the inverse of <code>chr()</code> for 8-bit strings.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='bitwise'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Bitwise Operations</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>~</code>, <code>&amp;</code>,
<code>|</code>, <code>^</code>,
<code>&lt;&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>~x</code></dd><dd><code>x &amp; y</code></dd><dd><code>x | y</code></dd><dd><code>x ^ y</code></dd><dd><code>x &lt;&lt; n</code></dd><dd><code>x &gt;&gt; n</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ~0 # binary: 000</pre></td><td><pre>-1 # binary: 111</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ~-1 # binary: 111</pre></td><td><pre>0 # binary: 000</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ~13 # binary: 01101</pre></td><td><pre>-14 # binary: 10010</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print -1 &amp; -1 # binary: 111 &amp; 111</pre></td><td><pre>-1 # binary: 111</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 14 &amp; 7 # binary: 01110 &amp; 00111</pre></td><td><pre>6 # binary: 00110</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 14 | 7 # binary: 01110 | 00111</pre></td><td><pre>15 # binary: 01111</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 14 ^ 7 # binary: 01110 ^ 00111</pre></td><td><pre>9 # binary: 01001</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 5 &lt;&lt; 3 # binary: 0101 &lt;&lt; 3</pre></td><td><pre>40 # binary: 0101000</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 23 &gt;&gt; 2 # binary: 010111 &lt;&lt; 2</pre></td><td><pre>5 # binary: 0101</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
These operators all use the underlying twos-complement
binary representation of the integral part of the
numbers <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
<code>~x</code> :
bitwise <i>not</i> (negation) of <code>x</code>
</li>
<li>
<code>x &amp; y</code> :
bitwise <i>and</i> (conjunction) of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>
</li>
<li>
<code>x | y</code> :
bitwise <i>or</i> (disjunction) of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>
</li>
<li>
<code>x ^ y</code> :
bitwise <i>exclusive or</i> of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>
</li>
<li>
<code>x &lt;&lt; n</code> :
bitwise <i>shift left</i> of <code>x</code> by <code>n</code> bits
</li>
<li>
<code>x &gt;&gt; n</code> :
bitwise <i>shift right</i> of <code>x</code>
by <code>n</code> bits
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion within Integers ... -->
</div> <!-- Closes Integers and Floating-Point Numbers -->

<h3 id='Booleans'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Booleans</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='bool'><code>bool</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='and'><code>and</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='or'><code>or</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='not'><code>not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='any'><code>any</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_logic_and_comparisons-booleans.py' target='_blank'>Booleans</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1b_logic_and_comparisons-logic.py' target='_blank'>Logic</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
Booleans represent the logical truth values <dfn>True</dfn>
and <dfn>False</dfn>.
Expressions that evaluate to Boolean values
are especially used as the tests in
conditionals (<code>if boolean_expr: &hellip;</code>).
</p>

<p>
While not encouraged, Booleans can also be used anywhere
that numbers can. <code>True</code> and <code>False</code>
are then treated as <code>1</code> and <code>0</code>,
respectively.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Booleans-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Boolean/Logical Constants</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>True</code></dd><dd><code>False</code></dd> </dl>

<p>
There are only two Boolean constants, <code>True</code>
and <code>False</code>. They must be capitalized
as shown.
</p>

<p>
In addition, the following constants are treated like
<code>False</code> in a logical expression:
</p>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li><code>None</code></li><li><code>0</code></li><li><code>0L</code></li><li><code>0.0</code></li><li><code>''</code></li><li><code>[]</code></li><li><code>()</code></li><li><code>{}</code></li><li><code>set([])</code></li></ul> <p>
All other values are treated like <code>True</code> in
logical expressions.
</p>

<p>
A values of a user-defined class is treated like
<code>False</code> if it has a <code>__nonzero__()</code>
method that returns <code>False</code> or if it has a
<code>__len__()</code> method that returns <code>0</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='bool'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Value into Boolean</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>bool</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>bool(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(1)</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(2.3)</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(0)</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool([])</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool([1, 2, 3])</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(())</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool((1, 2, 3))</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool('')</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool({})</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool({1: 2})</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(set([]))</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print bool(set([1, 2, 3]))</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns <code>True</code> for any
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Booleans-constants'>true-like</a>)
value, and <code>False</code> for any
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Booleans-constants'>false-like</a>)
value.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='and'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Logical Conjunction</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>and</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>x and y</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print True and True</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print False and True</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 1 and 2</pre></td><td><pre>2</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 0 and 2</pre></td><td><pre>0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
If <code>x</code> is <code>False</code> or any false-like
value, then this expression results in <code>x</code>,
otherwise this expression results in <code>y</code>.
</p>

<table class="truth center">
<tr>
<th><code>x</code></th>
<th><code>y</code></th>
<th class="left-border"><code>x and y</code></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>True</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>False</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>False</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>False</code></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<h3 id='or'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Logical Disjunction</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>or</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>x or y</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print True or True</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print False or True</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 1 or 2</pre></td><td><pre>1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 0 or 2</pre></td><td><pre>2</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
If <code>x</code> is <code>False</code> or any false-like
value, then this expression results in <code>y</code>,
otherwise it results in <code>x</code>.
</p>

<table class="truth center">
<tr>
<th><code>x</code></th>
<th><code>y</code></th>
<th class="left-border"><code>x or y</code></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>True</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>True</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>True</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>False</code></td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>
Note that in English, the word &ldquo;or&rdquo; is used in
two different ways. This operation represents
&ldquo;inclusive or&rdquo; (<code>x or y</code>),
where the result is <code>True</code> if
<em>at least one</em> argument is <code>True</code>.
In contrast, the &ldquo;exclusive or&rdquo;
(<code>x != y</code>) is <code>True</code>
if <em>exactly one</em> argument is <code>True</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='not'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Logical Negation</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>not</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>not x</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print not True</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print not False</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print not 2</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print not 0</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
If <code>x</code> is <code>False</code> or any
false-like value such as <code>0</code> or <code>[]</code>,
then this expression results in <code>True</code>,
otherwise it results in <code>False</code>.
</p>
<table class="truth center">
<tr>
<th><code>x</code></th>
<th class="left-border"><code>not x</code></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>True</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>False</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>False</code></td>
<td class="left-border"><code>True</code></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<h3 id='any'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Is Any Iterable Element True?</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>any</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>any(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print any([False, False, False])</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print any([False, True, False])</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print any([])</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print any((0, 3))</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print any('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='bool'><code>bool(x)</code></a> is <code>True</code> (or
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Booleans-constants'>true-like</a>)
for any element <code>x</code> in the iterable.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='all'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Are All Iterable Elements True?</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>all</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>all(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print all([False, True, False])</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print all([True, True, True])</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print all([])</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print all((0, 3))</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print all('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='bool'><code>bool(x)</code></a> is <code>True</code> (or
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Booleans-constants'>true-like</a>)
for all elements <code>x</code> in the iterable.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion within Booleans -->
</div> <!-- Closes Booleans -->
<h3 id='Strings'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Strings</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Sequences'>Sequences</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/introduction.html#strings' target='_blank'>Introduction: Strings</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-1a_codeskulptor-prints_strings_comments.py' target='_blank'>Comments, Strings, and Print</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3a_string_processing-operations.py' target='_blank'>String Operations</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3a_string_processing-input_checking.py' target='_blank'>Input Checking</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-strings-2.py' target='_blank'>Dollars and Cents</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-http://www.codeskulptor.org/more-3a_string_processing-initials.py' target='_blank'>Initials</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
<p>
A string is an immutable sequence of <dfn>characters</dfn>.
Many characters are familiar from what you can type
on a keyboard &mdash; a letter, a number, a symbol,
or a space.
The string with zero characters is called
<dfn>the empty string</dfn>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Strings-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>String Constants</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>"&hellip;"</code>,
<code>'&hellip;'</code>,
<code>"""&hellip;"""</code>,
<code>'''&hellip;'''</code>,
<code>r"&hellip;"</code>,
<code>r'&hellip;'</code>,
<code>r"""&hellip;"""</code>,
<code>r'''&hellip;'''</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>"&hellip;"</code></dd><dd><code>'&hellip;'</code></dd><dd><code>"""&hellip;"""</code></dd><dd><code>'''&hellip;'''</code></dd><dd><code>r"&hellip;"</code></dd><dd><code>r'&hellip;'</code></dd><dd><code>r"""&hellip;"""</code></dd><dd><code>r'''&hellip;'''</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ""</pre></td><td><pre> # The empty string.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'Hello, world.'</pre></td><td><pre>Hello, world.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print "Goodbye, cruel world."</pre></td><td><pre>Goodbye, cruel world.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print "It's a beautiful day."</pre></td><td><pre>It's a beautiful day.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print """This is
a multi-line
string."""</pre></td><td><pre>This is
a multi-line
string.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Typically, string constants are constructed within
a matched pair of
single or double quotes. A string with double quotes can
contain single quotes, often used as apostrophes.
Similarly, a string with single quotes can
contain double quotes.
</p>

<p>
Using a pair of triple-single or triple-double quotes
also creates a string, but also allows the string
to span over multiple lines.
These are primarily used as <dfn>documentation strings</dfn>
to document the purpose of a function, method, or class
definition.
</p>

<p>
Strings can contain
<a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII' target='_blank'>ASCII</a> characters.
</p>

<p>
Strings can contain escape sequences:
</p>
<table class='list'><tr><th><code>\'</code></th><td>single quote character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\&quot;</code></th><td>double quote character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\\</code></th><td>backslash character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\b</code></th><td>backspace character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\f</code></th><td>formfeed character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\n</code></th><td>new line character (starts a new line)</td></tr><tr><th><code>\r</code></th><td>carriage return character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\t</code></th><td>horizontal tab character (moves to next tab position, which is every eight characters)</td></tr><tr><th><code>\v</code></th><td>vertical tab character</td></tr><tr><th><code>\x<var>NN</var></code></th><td>ASCII character represented by a hexidecimal number <var>NN</var></td></tr></table>
<p>
However, <dfn>raw</dfn> strings, those preceded by an
<code>r</code>, do not recognize escape sequences.
Raw strings are typically used for
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-constants'>regular expressions</a>.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='str'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Value into String</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>str()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>str(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str()</pre></td><td><pre> # The empty list</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str(4859202)</pre></td><td><pre>4859202</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str(True)</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>abc</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str(None)</pre></td><td><pre>None</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str((1, 2, 3, 4, 5))</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str({1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'})</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str(set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]))</pre></td><td><pre>set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print str(str)</pre></td><td><pre>&lt;class 'str'&gt;</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>class Silly:
def __init__(self, x):
self.x = x

print repr(Silly(3))</pre></td><td><pre>&lt;__main__.Silly object&gt;</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>class Silly:
def __init__(self, x):
self.x = x
def __str__(self):
return 'Silly' + str(self.x)

print str(Silly(3))</pre></td><td><pre>Silly3</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr()</code></a> &mdash; Emphasizes unambiguity</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a string that is a printable representation of
object <code>an_obj</code>.
The intent is that this string should be human-readable.
For built-in types, this
is the normal printed representation. For user-defined
types, this defaults to a string in angle brackets
that includes the type of the object.
However, a class can specify what this function returns
for its instances by defining a <code>__str__()</code>
method.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='repr'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unambiguous Printable Representation of Object</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>repr()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>repr(an_obj)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print repr([3, 5, 9])</pre></td><td><pre>[3, 5, 9]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>class Silly:
def __init__(self, x):
self.x = x

print repr(Silly(3))</pre></td><td><pre>&lt;__main__.Silly object&gt;</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>class Silly:
def __init__(self, x):
self.x = x
def __repr__(self):
return 'Silly' + str(self.x)

print repr(Silly(3))</pre></td><td><pre>Silly3</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str()</code></a> &mdash; Emphasizes readability</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a string that is a printable representation of
object <code>an_obj</code>.
The intent is that this string should be unambiguous.
For built-in types, this
is the normal printed representation. For user-defined
types, this defaults to a string in angle brackets
that includes the type of the object.
However, a class can specify what this function returns
for its instances by defining a <code>__repr__()</code>
method.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-formatting'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Format String</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>%</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str % value</code></dd><dd><code>a_str % a_tuple</code></dd><dd><code>a_str % a_dict</code></dd><dt>Documentation:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/library/stdtypes.html#string-formatting' target='_blank'>String Formatting Operations</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
</div>
<h3 id='string-join'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Concatenate Iterable Sequences into Strings</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.join()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.join([iterable])</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ','.join('abcd')</pre></td><td><pre>a,b,c,d</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' '.join(['a', 'bc', 'd'])</pre></td><td><pre>a bc d</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'zz'.join(('a', 'bc', 'd'))</pre></td><td><pre>azzbczzd</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' '.join({'a': 'x', 'b': 'y'})</pre></td><td><pre>a b</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' '.join(set(['a', 'b']))</pre></td><td><pre>a b</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a string which is the concatenation
of the strings in the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>iterable</a>.
The string <code>a_str</code> is concatenated
between the other strings as a separator.
</p>

<p>
Most commonly used to combine a list of strings into
a single string.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='string-capitalize'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Capitalize String</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.capitalize()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.capitalize()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'peAr'.capitalize()</pre></td><td><pre>Pear</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Return a copy of the string <code>a_str</code> with its
first character capitalized and the rest lower-cased.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-case'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Change Case of String</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.upper()</code>,
<code>a_str.lower()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.upper()</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.lower()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abc123DEF'.upper()</pre></td><td><pre>ABC123DEF</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abc123DEF'.lower()</pre></td><td><pre>abc123def</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a copy of the string <code>a_str</code>
with all the cased
characters converted to upper- or lowercase, respectively
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='string-replace'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Replace Substring</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.replace()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.replace(old, new)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.replace(old, new, maxreplace)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.replace('bc', 'f')</pre></td><td><pre>afdafd</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.replace('bc', 'f', 1)</pre></td><td><pre>afdabcd</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.replace('g', 'f')</pre></td><td><pre>abcdabcd</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'aaaaa'.replace('aa', 'f')</pre></td><td><pre>ffa</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a copy of the string <code>a_str</code>
with all occurrences of
substring <code>old</code> replaced by <code>new</code>.
If the optional argument <code>maxreplace</code> is given,
then the first at most <code>maxreplace</code>
occurrences are replaced.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='string-find'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Find Substring</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.find()</code>,
<code>a_str.rfind()</code>,
<code>a_str.index()</code>,
<code>a_str.rindex()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.find(sub)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.find(sub, start)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.find(sub, start, end)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rfind(sub)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rfind(sub, start)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rfind(sub, start, end)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.index(sub)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.index(sub, start)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.index(sub, start, end)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rindex(sub)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rindex(sub, start)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rindex(sub, start, end)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('bc')</pre></td><td><pre>1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('bc', 3)</pre></td><td><pre>5</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('bc', 3, 6)</pre></td><td><pre>5</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.rfind('bc')</pre></td><td><pre>5</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.rfind('bc', 3)</pre></td><td><pre>5</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('f')</pre></td><td><pre>-1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.rfind('f')</pre></td><td><pre>-1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('bc', 6)</pre></td><td><pre>-1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.rfind('bc', 6)</pre></td><td><pre>-1</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcdabcd'.find('bc', 3, 5)</pre></td><td><pre>-1</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the highest index in the string
<code>a_str</code> where substring
<code>sub</code> is found, such that <code>sub</code>
is contained within
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-slice'><code>a_str[start:end]</code></a>,
where <code>start</code> defaults to 0, and
<code>end</code> defaults to the length of
<code>a_str</code>.
</p>

<p>
If the substring isn't found,
<code>a_str.find()</code> and
<code>a_str.rfind()</code> each return -1, while
<code>a_str.index()</code> and
<code>a_str.rindex()</code> each raise an error.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-partition'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Split String at One Delimeter</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.partition()</code>,
<code>a_str.rpartition()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.partition(sep)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rpartition(sep)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a b c'.partition(' ')</pre></td><td><pre>('a', ' ', 'b c')</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a b c'.rpartition(' ')</pre></td><td><pre>('a b', ' ', 'c')</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-split'><code>a_str.split()</code></a> &mdash; Splits multiple times</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-split'><code>re.split()</code></a> &mdash; Splits on more general patterns</dd> ?>
</dl>

<p>
Splits the string <code>a_str</code>
at the first (<code>partition</code>)
or last (<code>rpartition</code>) occurrence of
substring <code>sep</code>, and returns a 3-tuple
containing the part before the separator,
the separator itself, and the part after the separator.
If the separator is not found,
returns a 3-tuple containing two empty strings,
followed by the string itself.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-split'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Split String at Multiple Delimeters</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.split()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.split()</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.split(sep)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.split(sep, maxsplit)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a bc d'.split()</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'bc', 'd']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a bc d'.split(None)</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'bc', 'd']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a bc d'.split(' ')</pre></td><td><pre>['a', '', '', 'bc', 'd']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a bc d'.split(' ')</pre></td><td><pre>['a', ' bc d']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'a bc d'.split('b')</pre></td><td><pre>['a ', 'c d']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'ababbaaaa'.split('a', 2)</pre></td><td><pre>['', 'b', 'bbaaaa']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-partition'><code>a_str.partition()</code>, etc.</a> &mdash; Splits only once</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-split'><code>re.split()</code></a> &mdash; Splits on more general patterns</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a list of the words in the string
<code>a_str</code>,
using <code>sep</code> as the delimiter string.
If <code>maxsplit</code> is given, at most
<code>maxsplit</code> splits are done, the leftmost ones.
If <code>sep</code> is not specified or is <code>None</code>,
any whitespace string is a separator.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='string-isdigit'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Test String for Digits</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.isdigit()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.isdigit()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ''.isdigit()</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print '1234'.isdigit()</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print '1234abc'.isdigit()</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether all characters in the
string <code>a_str</code> are digits
and that there is at least one character in the string.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-alignment'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Align String</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.center()</code>,
<code>a_str.ljust()</code>,
<code>a_str.rjust()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.center(width)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.center(width, fillchar)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.ljust(width)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.ljust(width, fillchar)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rjust(width)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.center(width, fillchar)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print '*' + 'abcd'.center(30) + '*'</pre></td><td><pre>* abcd *</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcd'.ljust(30) + '*'</pre></td><td><pre>abcd *</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcd'.rjust(30)</pre></td><td><pre> abcd</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print '*' + 'abcd'.center(30, 'x') + '*'</pre></td><td><pre>*xxxxxxxxxxxxxabcdxxxxxxxxxxxxx*</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcd'.ljust(30, 'x') + '*'</pre></td><td><pre>abcdxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx*</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'abcd'.rjust(30, 'x')</pre></td><td><pre>xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxabcd</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns <code>a_str</code> aligned
in a string of length width.
The fill character defaults to a space.
<code>a_str.center()</code> centers the string,
<code>a_str.ljust()</code> left justifies it, and
<code>a_str.rjust()</code> right justifies it.
</p>

<p>
These are typically used in simple output formatting
to produce fixed-width columns.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-startswith'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Check Prefix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.startswith()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.startswith(prefix)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'silly string'.startswith('sil')</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'silly string'.startswith('ing')</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-endswith'><code>a_str.endswith()</code></a> &mdash; Checks suffix</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether the string <code>a_str</code> begins
with the string <code>prefix</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-endswith'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Check Suffix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.endswith()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.endswith(suffix)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'silly string'.endswith('sil')</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'silly string'.endswith('ing')</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-startswith'><code>a_str.startswith()</code></a> &mdash; Checks prefix</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether the string <code>a_str</code> ends
with the string <code>suffix</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='string-strip'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Remove Leading and Trailing Characters</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_str.strip()</code>,
<code>a_str.lstrip()</code>,
<code>a_str.rstrip()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_str.strip(s)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.strip(s, chars)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.lstrip(s)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.lstrip(s, chars)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rstrip(s)</code></dd><dd><code>a_str.rstrip(s, chars)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' cde fgh '.strip()</pre></td><td><pre>cde fgh</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' cde fgh '.strip(None)</pre></td><td><pre>cde fgh</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'aaababcdeababfghbaba'.strip('ab')</pre></td><td><pre>cdeababfgh</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' cde fgh '.lstrip()</pre></td><td><pre>cde fgh </pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'aaababcdeababfghbaba'.lstrip('ab')</pre></td><td><pre>cdeababfghbaba</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ' cde fgh '.rstrip()</pre></td><td><pre> cde fgh</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print 'aaababcdeababfghbaba'.rstrip('ab')</pre></td><td><pre>aaababcdeababfgh</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
These return a new string like <code>a_str</code>
except that leading (<code>a_str.lstrip()</code>),
trailing (<code>a_str.rstrip()</code>), or both
(<code>a_str.strip()</code>) characters are removed.
They remove any characters given in <code>chars</code>,
which defaults to any whitespace characters.
Also, if <code>chars</code> is <code>None</code>,
these also remove whitespace characters.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Strings-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported String Operations and Constants</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li>Escape sequences <code>\a</code> and octal</li><li><code>__str__()</code> on built-in types</li><li><code>__repr__()</code> on built-in types</li><li><code>eval()</code></li><li><code>intern()</code></li><li><code>a_str.replace(old, new, count)</code></li><li><code>a_str.split(sep, maxsplit)</code></li><li><code>a_str.startswith(prefix)</code> with a tuple argument</li><li><code>a_str.startswith(prefix, start)</code></li><li><code>a_str.startswith(prefix, start, end)</code></li><li><code>a_str.endswith(suffix)</code> with a tuple argument</li><li><code>a_str.endswith(suffix, start)</code></li><li><code>a_str.endswith(suffix, start, end)</code></li><li><code>a_str.decode()</code></li><li><code>a_str.encode()</code></li><li><code>a_str.expandtabs()</code></li><li><code>a_str.format()</code></li><li><code>a_str.isalnum()</code></li><li><code>a_str.isalpha()</code></li><li><code>a_str.islower()</code></li><li><code>a_str.isspace()</code></li><li><code>a_str.istitle()</code></li><li><code>a_str.isupper()</code></li><li><code>a_str.rsplit()</code></li><li><code>a_str.splitlines()</code></li><li><code>a_str.swapcase()</code></li><li><code>a_str.title()</code></li><li><code>a_str.translate()</code></li><li><code>a_str.zfill()</code></li><li><code>eval()</code></li></ul> </div>

<h3 id='Lists'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Lists</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list'><code>list</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-__setitem__'><code>[]=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='range'><code>range</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-append'><code>a_list.append</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-extend'><code>a_list.extend</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-insert'><code>a_list.insert</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-remove'><code>a_list.remove</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-pop'><code>a_list.pop</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-reverse'><code>a_list.reverse</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-sort'><code>a_list.sort</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-concatenation'><code>+</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal'
