data-dest='any'><code>any</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-join'><code>a_str.join</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='enumerate'><code>enumerate</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Sequences'>Sequences</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Tutorials:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/introduction.html#lists' target='_blank'>Introduction: Lists</a></li><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/datastructures.html#more-on-lists' target='_blank'>Data Structures: More on Lists</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-structure.py' target='_blank'>Lists</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-list_methods.py' target='_blank'>List Methods</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_lists-more_methods.py' target='_blank'>More List Methods</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-true_false_quiz.py' target='_blank'>True-False Quiz</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-silly_words.py' target='_blank'>Silly Words</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-rainbow_canvas.py' target='_blank'>Rainbow Canvas</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-digital_numbers.py' target='_blank'>Digital Numbers</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-collisions_and_reflections.py' target='_blank'>Ball Reflection</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Tuples'>Tuples</a> &mdash; Immutable sequences</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Dictionaries'>Dictionaries</a> &mdash; More flexible indexing</dd> </dl>
<p>
A list is a mutable sequence of values of any type.
A list with zero elements is called <dfn>an empty list</dfn>.
List elements are indexed by sequential integers, starting
with zero.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Lists-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>List Constants</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>[&hellip;]</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>[val<sub>0</sub>, val<sub>1</sub>, &hellip;]</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print []</pre></td><td><pre>[]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print [1, 2, 3, 8, 9]</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 8, 9]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print [(1, 2), 'hello', 3, ['a', 'b', 'c']]</pre></td><td><pre>[(1, 2), 'hello', 3, ['a', 'b', 'c']]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Lists are constructed with square brackets,
separating items with commas.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Iterable or Iterator into List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>list()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>list()</code></dd><dd><code>list(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list()</pre></td><td><pre>[]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>['a' ,'b', 'c']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list((1, 2, 3, 4, 5))</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list(set([1, 2, 3, 4]))</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list({1: 2, 3: 4})</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 3]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print list(enumerate(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']))</pre></td><td><pre>[(0, 'a'), (1, 'b'), (2, 'c'), (3, 'd')]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Converts any iterable or iterator into a list.
If the argument is already a list, it returns a copy,
i.e., a new list with the same elements.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='list-__setitem__'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set Value at Specific Position in List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list[]=</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list[index] = value</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>numbers = [4, 8, 19, 0]
numbers[1] = 27
print numbers</pre></td><td><pre>[4, 27, 19, 0]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Mutates the list to now contain the given value
at the given index.
The index must be within the current range of indices
of the list.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='range'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Arithmetic Progressions List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>range()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>range(stop)</code></dd><dd><code>range(start, stop)</code></dd><dd><code>range(start, stop, step)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print range(5)</pre></td><td><pre>[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print range(1, 10)</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print range(-10, 100, 20)</pre></td><td><pre>[-10, 10, 30, 50, 70, 90]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print range(100, -10, -20)</pre></td><td><pre>[100, 80, 60, 40, 20, 0]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>for i in range(5):
print i</pre></td><td><pre>0
1
2
3
4</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
This is a versatile function to create lists containing
arithmetic progressions.
The <code>step</code> cannot be zero, and
it defaults to 1.
The <code>start</code> defaults to 0.
The full form returns a list of integers
<code>[start, start + step, start + 2 * step, &hellip;]</code>.
If <code>step</code> is positive, the last element
is the largest <code>start + i * step</code>
less than <code>stop</code>;
if <code>step</code> is negative, the last element is
the smallest <code>start + i * step</code> greater than
<code>stop</code>.
</p>

<p>
It is often used in <code>for</code> loops, as illustrated
in the last example above. It provides a mechanism for
looping a specific number of iterations.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='list-append'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Item to End of List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.append()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.append(x)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [1, 2, 3]
a_list.append(4)
a_list.append([5, 6, 7])
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, [5, 6, 7]]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>list1 = [1, 2, 3]
list2 = [1, 2, 3]
list1.append([4, 5, 6])
list2.extend([4, 5, 6])
print list1
print list2</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, [4, 5, 6]]
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Add item <code>x</code> to the end of the
list <code>a_list</code>.
</p>

<p>
A common mistake is to confuse
<code>a_list.append(x)</code> and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='list-extend'><code>a_list.extend(x)</code></a>.
As shown in the last example above,
the former adds <em>one</em> element to the list,
while the latter adds a <em>group</em> of elements.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-extend'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Multiple Items to End of List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.extend()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.extend(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [1, 2, 3]
a_list.extend([])
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [1, 2, 3]
a_list.extend([4, 5, 6])
a_list.extend((7, 8))
a_list.extend('abc')
a_list.extend({'d': 'e', 'f': 'g'})</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 'a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'f']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>list1 = [1, 2, 3]
list2 = [1, 2, 3]
list1.append([4, 5, 6])
list2.extend([4, 5, 6])
print list1
print list2</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3, [4, 5, 6]]
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Add each item from the iterable <code>an_iter</code> onto
the end of the list <code>a_list</code>.
When the iterable is a list, this is also called
concatenation.
</p>

<p>
A common mistake is to confuse
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='append'><code>a_list.append(x)</code></a> and <code>a_list.extend(x)</code>.
As shown in the last example above,
the former adds <em>one</em> element to the list,
while the latter adds a <em>group</em> of elements.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-insert'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Insert Item into List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.insert()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.insert(i, x)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = ['a', 'b', 'c']
a_list.insert(1, 'x')
print a_list
a_list.insert(0, 'y')
print a_list
a_list.insert(5, 'z')
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'x', 'b', 'c']
['y', 'a', 'x', 'b', 'c']
['y', 'a', 'x', 'b', 'c', 'z']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Inserts an item at a given position.
The first argument is the index of the element
before which to insert, so <code>a.insert(0, x)</code>
inserts at the front of the list,
and <code>a.insert(len(a), x)</code>
is equivalent to <code>a.append(x)</code>.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-remove'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Remove Item from List by Value</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.remove()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.remove(x)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'b']
a_list.remove('b')
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'c', 'b']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Removes the first item from the list whose value is
<code>x</code>. It is an error if there is no such item.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-pop'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Remove Item from List by Position</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.pop()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.pop([index])</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = ['a', 'b', 'c']
print a_list.pop(1)
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>b
['a', 'c']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Removes the item at the given index in the list
<code>a_list</code>,
and returns it. If no index is specified, it
defaults to the last item.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-reverse'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Reverse Items in List</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.reverse()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.reverse()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [1, 2, 3]
a_list.reverse()
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>[3, 2, 1]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Reverses the elements of the list <code>a_list</code>
in place.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='list-sort'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Sort Items in List in Place</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_list.sort()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_list.sort()</code></dd><dd><code>a_list.sort(reverse=rev_bool, key=key_fn)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [2, 1, 3, 2]
a_list.sort()
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 2, 3]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>a_list = [2, 1, 3, 2]
a_list.sort(reverse=True)
print a_list</pre></td><td><pre>[3, 2, 2, 1]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sorted'><code>sorted()</code></a> &mdash; Sort an iterable</dd> </dl>
<p>
Sorts the items of the list <code>a_list</code>
in ascending order in place.
I.e., it mutates <code>a_list</code>.
It returns <code>None</code>.
</p>

<p>
By default or when <code>rev_bool</code>
is <code>False</code>, the elements are in ascending order.
When <code>rev_bool</code> is <code>True</code>,
the elements are in descending order.
(Bug: It reverses when <code>rev_bool</code> is <code>False</code>, too.)
If the elements are of different types, then
the ascending or descending ordering is based upon their
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='values-objects'>hash values</a>.
</p>

<p>
<em>Need to explain and provide examples for key argument.</em>
</p>

<p>
The sort is guaranteed to be stable.
Thus, when multiple elements have the same key, their
original order is preserved.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion within Lists -->
</div> <!-- Closes Lists -->
<h3 id='Tuples'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Tuples</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">

data-dest='numeric-shape'><code>a_matrix.shape</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-concatenation'><code>+</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-copies'><code>*</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-__getitem__'><code>[]</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-slice'><code>[:]</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-slice'><code>[::]</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-index'><code>a_seq.index</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='seq-count'><code>a_seq.count</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Sequences'>Sequences</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/datastructures.html#tuples-and-sequences' target='_blank'>Data Structures: Tuples</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_lists-tuples.py' target='_blank'>Tuples</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lists'>Lists</a> &mdash; Mutable sequences</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Strings'>Strings</a> &mdash; Specialized to only containing text</dd> </dl>
<p>
A tuple is an immutable sequence of values of any type.
Tuple elements are indexed by sequential integers, starting
with zero.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Tuples-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Tuple Constants</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>(&hellip;)</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>(val<sub>0</sub>, val<sub>1</sub>, &hellip;)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ()</pre></td><td><pre>()</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print (1,)</pre></td><td><pre>(1,)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>t = 1,
print t</pre></td><td><pre>(1,)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print (1, 2, 3, 8, 9)</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 8, 9)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>t = 1, 2, 3, 8, 9
print t</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 8, 9)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print ((1, 2), 'hello', 3, ['a', 'b', 'c'])</pre></td><td><pre>((1, 2), 'hello', 3, ['a', 'b', 'c'])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>t = 1, 2, 3
print t</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3)</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Tuples are constructed by the comma operator,
with or without enclosing parentheses.
An empty tuple must have the enclosing parentheses.
A single item tuple must have a trailing comma.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='tuple'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Iterable into Tuple</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>tuple()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>tuple()</code></dd><dd><code>tuple(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple()</pre></td><td><pre>()</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>('a' ,'b', 'c')</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple((1, 2, 3, 4, 5))</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple(set([1, 2, 3, 4]))</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 2, 3, 4)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple({1: 2, 3: 4})</pre></td><td><pre>(1, 3)</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print tuple(enumerate(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']))</pre></td><td><pre>((0, 'a'), (1, 'b'), (2, 'c'), (3, 'd'))</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Converts any iterable into a tuple.
If the argument is already a tuple, it returns a copy,
i.e., a new tuple with the same elements.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Tuple-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported Tuple Operation</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li>coerce()</li></ul> </div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion within Tuples -->
</div> <!-- Closes Tuples -->

<h3 id='Dictionaries'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Dictionaries</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict'><code>dict</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-get'><code>a_dict.get</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-get'><code>[]</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-__setitem__'><code>[]=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-has_key'><code>a_dict.has_key</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-pop'><code>a_dict.pop</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-items'><code>a_dict.items</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-keys'><code>a_dict.keys</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dict-values'><code>a_dict.values</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-in'><code>in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-not-in'><code>not in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-len'><code>len</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sum'><code>sum</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-max'><code>max</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-min'><code>min</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-zip'><code>zip</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sorted'><code>sorted</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-map'><code>map</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-filter'><code>filter</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-reduce'><code>reduce</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='any'><code>any</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-join'><code>a_str.join</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='enumerate'><code>enumerate</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Subclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='DefaultDictionaries'>Default Dictionaries</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Counters'>Counters</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/datastructures.html#dictionaries' target='_blank'>Data Structures: Dictionaries</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-dictionaries.py' target='_blank'>Cipher</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_dictionaries-secret_code.py' target='_blank'>Secret Code</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_dictionaries-shape_colors.py' target='_blank'>Shape Colors</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lists'>Lists</a> &mdash; Specialized to keys 0, 1, &hellip;</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Sets'>Sets</a> &mdash; Essentially dictionaries specialized to Boolean values</dd> </dl>

<p>
A dictionary is a mutable mapping from <dfn>keys</dfn>
to values.
A dictionary with no keys is called
<dfn>an empty dictionary</dfn>.
Dictionaries are also known in some programming languages as
<dfn>associative memories</dfn>,
<dfn>associative arrays</dfn>, or <dfn>hashmaps</dfn>.
Unlike sequences, which are indexed by a range of integers,
dictionaries are indexed by keys, which can be of any
immutable type.
Thus, dictionaries are also unordered.
When printed, iterated upon, or converted into a sequence, its
elements will appear in an arbitrary, implementation-dependent
order.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Dictionaries-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Dictionary Constants</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>{}</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>{key<sub>0</sub>: value<sub>0</sub>, key<sub>1</sub>: value<sub>1</sub>, &hellip; }</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {}</pre></td><td><pre>{}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 9: 'c'}</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 9: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', (5, 'item'): [100], 'key': {True: 'hello', -9: 0}}</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', (5, 'item'): [100], 'key': {True: 'hello', -9: 0}}</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
A dictionary is an unordered collection of
<code>key: value</code> pairs, with each key in a
dictionary being distinct.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Iterable of Pairs into Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>dict()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>dict()</code></dd><dd><code>dict(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict()</pre></td><td><pre>{}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict([(1, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (3, 'c')])</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict(((1, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (3, 'c'), (3, 'd')))</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'd'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict(set([(1, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (3, 'c')]))</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict({1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'})</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print dict(enumerate(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']))</pre></td><td><pre>{0: 'a', 1: 'b', 2: 'c', 3: 'd'}</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a new dictionary with the data from
<code>an_iter</code>.
The iterable or iterator <code>an_iter</code> must consist of
pairs of a valid key (i.e., of immutable type) and value.
If any key occurs multiple times, then the last value
encountered for that key will be in the resulting dictionary.
If <code>an_iter</code> is already a dictionary,
it returns a copy,
i.e., a new dictionary with the same elements.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-get'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Value in Dictionary by Key</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict[]</code>,
<code>a_dict.get()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict[key]</code></dd><dd><code>a_dict.get(key)</code></dd><dd><code>a_dict.get(key, default)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}[2]</pre></td><td><pre>b</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.get(2)</pre></td><td><pre>b</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.get(7)</pre></td><td><pre>None</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.get(7, 'not here')</pre></td><td><pre>not here</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns the value associated with the given key the
dictionary <code>a_dict</code>.
</p>

<p>
If the key is not in the dictionary,
<code>a_dict[key]</code> raises a
<code>KeyError</code> error.
However, <code>a_dict.get(key)</code> returns the
default value <code>default</code> if provided, and
<code>None</code> otherwise.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-__setitem__'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set Value for Key in Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict[key] = value</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict[key] = value</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>d = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
d[2] = 'd'
print d
d[5] = 'e'
print d</pre></td><td><pre>{1: 'a', 2: 'd', 3: 'c'}
{1: 'a', 2: 'd', 3: 'c', 5: 'e'}</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Mutates the dictionary <code>a_dict</code>
so that the given key now maps to the given value.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='dict-has_key'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Check if Key is in Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict.has_key()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict.has_key(key)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.has_key(2)</pre></td><td><pre>True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.has_key(4)</pre></td><td><pre>False</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns whether the given key is a key in the dictionary
<code>a_dict</code>. The equivalent
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-in'><code>key in a_dict</code></a> is considered better style.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-pop'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Remove Key from Dictionary and Return its Value</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict.pop()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict.pop(key)</code></dd><dd><code>a_dict.pop(key, default)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>d = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
print d.pop(1)
print d</pre></td><td><pre>a
{2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>d = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
print d.pop(1, 'xyz')
print d</pre></td><td><pre>a
{2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>d = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
print d.pop(4)
print d</pre></td><td><pre>Line 2: KeyError: 4</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>d = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
print d.pop(4, 'xyz')
print d</pre></td><td><pre>xyz
{1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
If <code>key</code> is a key in the dictionary, this
removes it from the dictionary and returns its value.
The value <code>default</code> is ignored in this case.
</p>

<p>
If <code>key</code> is not a key in the dictionary,
this returns the value <code>default</code>.
If no default is provided, a <code>KeyError</code> is raised.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-items'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get List of all Key/Value Pairs in Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict.items()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict.items()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.items()</pre></td><td><pre>[(1, 'a'), (2, 'b'), (3, 'c')]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>sample_dict = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
for key, value in sample_dict.items():
print key, 'maps to', value</pre></td><td><pre>1 maps to a
2 maps to b
3 maps to c</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a list of <code>(key, value)</code> pairs,
for all the keys in dictionary <code>a_dict</code>.
</p>

<p>
A common usage is to loop over all
key/value pairs in a dictionary, as in the last example
above.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-keys'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get List of all Keys in Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict.keys()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict.keys()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.keys()</pre></td><td><pre>[1, 2, 3]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns a list of the keys in dictionary
<code>a_dict</code>.
</p>

<p>
While you can test if something is a dictionary key
explicitly, like
<code>key in a_dict.keys()</code>, the
simpler expression <code>key in a_dict</code> is
equivalent. The same applies to <code>for</code>-loops.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='dict-values'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get List of all Values in Dictionary</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_dict.values()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_dict.values()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}.values()</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'b', 'c']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>sample_dict = {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}
for value in sample_dict.values():
print value, 'is a value in the dictionary'</pre></td><td><pre>a is a value in the dictionary
b is a value in the dictionary
c is a value in the dictionary</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a list of the values in dictionary
<code>a_dict</code>.
</p>

<p>
A common usage is to loop over all
values in a dictionary, as in the last example above.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Sets'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Sets</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set'><code>a_set.set</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-union'><code>a_set.union</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-intersection'><code>a_set.intersection</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-difference'><code>a_set.difference</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-symmetric_difference'><code>a_set.symmetric_difference</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-update'><code>a_set.update</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-intersection_update'><code>a_set.intersection_update</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-difference_update'><code>a_set.difference_update</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-symmetric_difference_update'><code>a_set.symmetric_difference_update</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-add'><code>a_set.add</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-remove'><code>a_set.remove</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-remove'><code>a_set.discard</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-pop'><code>a_set.pop</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-issubset'><code>a_set.issubset</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-issuperset'><code>a_set.issuperset</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-copy'><code>a_set.copy</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-in'><code>in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-not-in'><code>not in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-len'><code>len</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sum'><code>sum</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-max'><code>max</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-min'><code>min</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-join'><code>a_str.join</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='enumerate'><code>enumerate</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/datastructures.html#sets' target='_blank'>Data Structures: Sets</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
<p>
A set is an unordered collection without duplicates.
When printed, iterated upon, or converted into a sequence, its
elements will appear in an arbitrary, implementation-dependent
order.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='set'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Convert Iterable into Set</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>set()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>set()</code></dd><dd><code>set(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set()</pre></td><td><pre>set([])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set('abc')</pre></td><td><pre>set(['a' ,'b', 'c'])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 3, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set((1, 2, 3, 4, 5))</pre></td><td><pre>set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set(set([1, 2, 3, 4]))</pre></td><td><pre>set([1, 2, 3, 4])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set({1: 2, 3: 4})</pre></td><td><pre>set([1, 3])</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print set(enumerate(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']))</pre></td><td><pre>set([(0, 'a'), (1, 'b'), (2, 'c'), (3, 'd')])</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a new set with the values from iterable or iterator
<code>an_iter</code>.
If the argument is already a set, it returns a copy,
i.e., a new set with the same elements.
</p>
</div>

the set of elements in iterable <code>an_iter</code>.

<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_set.remove(x)</code></dd><dd><code>a_set.discard(x)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>s = set([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])

<h3 id='Functions'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Functions &amp; Methods</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> emitAddExamples(array(
"Function Structure (<code>def</code>)" => "more-1b_functions-structure.py",
"More Functions" => "more-1b_functions-examples.py"));
</dl>

<p>
A <dfn>function</dfn> is a parameterized section of code.
A <dfn>method</dfn> is simply a function which is an
attribute of an object, i.e., defined as part of a class.
Functions and methods are values themselves.
(However, CodeSkulptor does not yet consider built-in functions
to be values.)
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='def-return'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Named Functions</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>def a_func(): &hellip;</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>def a_func(var0, var1, &hellip;):
&hellip;</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def is_even(n):
'''Returns a Boolean indicating whether n is even.'''
return n % 2 == 0

print is_even
print is_even(2)</pre></td><td><pre>&lt;function is_even&gt;
True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def median_3(a, b, c):
'''Returns the median (middle) of the three arguments.'''

if a &lt;= b:
if b &lt;= c:
return b
elif a &lt;= c:
return c
else:
return a
else:
if a &lt; c:
return a
elif b &lt; c:
return c
else:
return b

print median_3(5, 9, 2)</pre></td><td><pre>5</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def swap_list_elts(l, index1, index2):
'''Swaps l[index1] and l[index2]'''

l[index1], l[index2] = l[index2], l[index1]

l = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']
print swap_list_elts(l, 1, 3)
print l</pre></td><td><pre>None
['a', 'd', 'c', 'b']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def add2(n):
'''Returns the given value plus 2.'''
return n + 2

print map(add2, [1, 3, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>[3, 5, 7]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/controlflow.html#defining-functions' target='_blank'>Defining Functions</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
Creates a function named by <code>a_func</code>.
When applied
to arguments, the code in the function body is run
until a <code>return</code> statement is reached or the
end of the code is reached. In the former case, the function
returns the value specified in the <code>return</code>,
while in the latter case, the function returns
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='NoneType'><code>None</code></a>.
</p>

<p>
To be distinct from a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='def-yield'>generator function</a>,
the body must not contain <code>yield</code> statements.
</p>

<p>
For good style, each named function should also have a
<dfn>documentation string</dfn> (docstring)
immediately after its header, as illustrated in the examples.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='lambda-return'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Anonymous Functions</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>lambda (): &hellip;</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>lambda var1, var2, &hellip;: expr</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>is_even = lambda n : n % 2 == 0

print is_even
print is_even(2)</pre></td><td><pre>&lt;function &lt;lambda&gt;&gt;
True</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>print map(lambda n: n + 2, [1, 3, 5])</pre></td><td><pre>[3, 5, 7]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Tutorial:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/controlflow.html#lambda-forms' target='_blank'>Lambda Forms</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
Anonymous functions are simplified forms of function
definitions. First, they do not have a name.
Second, the parameter list is not in parentheses.
And third, the function body is just a single expression,
which is implicitly returned.
This simplicity is convenient especially
when the function is simply passed
as an argument, as in the last example above.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='func-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported Function and Method Operations</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li>Built-in functions and methods are not values.</li><li>Keyword arguments are not supported.</li><li><code>classmethod()</code></li><li><code>staticmethod()</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_doc</code></li><li><code>a_func.__doc__</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_name</code></li><li><code>a_func.__name__</code></li><li><code>a_func.__module__</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_defaults</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_code</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_globals</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_dict</code></li><li><code>a_func.func_closure</code></li></ul> </div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in Functions -->
</div> <!-- Closes Functions -->

<h3 id='Generators'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Generators</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='send'><code>a_gen.send</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='next'><code>an_iter.next</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Counter-elements'><code>a_counter.elements</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-in'><code>in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-not-in'><code>not in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-len'><code>len</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sum'><code>sum</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-max'><code>max</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-min'><code>min</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-zip'><code>zip</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sorted'><code>sorted</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-map'><code>map</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-filter'><code>filter</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-reduce'><code>reduce</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='any'><code>any</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-join'><code>a_str.join</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='enumerate'><code>enumerate</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterators'>Iterators</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
Generators are a kind of iterator that are defined like
functions. A <dfn>generator function</dfn> looks just like
a regular function, except that it uses <code>yield</code>
instead of <code>return</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='def-yield'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Generator Functions</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>def a_genfunc(): &hellip; yield &hellip;</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>def a_genfunc(var0, var1, &hellip;):
&hellip;
yield &hellip;
&hellip;</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def squares(n):
'''Yields the squares from 0 to n-1 squared.'''

for i in range(n):
yield i * i

g = squares(4)
print g.next()
print g.next()
print g.next()
print g.next()</pre></td><td><pre>0
1
4
9</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd>
<p>
Creates a generator function named by <code>an_iter</code>.
When applied to arguments, the code in the function body
is encapsulated and returned as a generator,
a type of iterator. Each time the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='next'><code>next()</code></a>,
method is applied to the resulting generator,
the code is run until the next <code>yield</code>
expression, and the <code>yield</code> expression's
value is returned from that method call.
Thus, the creation of the generator does not wait for
<em>all</em> of its elements to be generator,
and the generator could even represent an infinite number of
elements.
</p>

<p>
To be distinct from a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='def-function'>function definition</a>,
the body must contain <code>yield</code> statements,
not <code>return</code> statements.
</p>

<p>
For good style, each generator function should also have a
<dfn>documentation string</dfn> (docstring)
immediately after its header, as illustrated in the example.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='send'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Next Element and Send Value to Generator</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_gen.send()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_gen.send(val)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def foo():
x = yield 1
print 'Yielded:', x
yield 2
bar = foo()
print bar.next()
print bar.send('Hi!')</pre></td><td><pre>1
Yielded: Hi!
2</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>def add1genf(n):
while n != None:
print 'Before:', n
n = yield n + 1
print 'After:', n
add1gen = add1genf(10)
print '---'
print add1gen.send('This first value is ignored.')
print '---'
print add1gen.send(3)
print '---'
print add1gen.send(17)</pre></td><td><pre>---
Before: 10
11
---
After: 3
Before: 3
4
---
After: 17
Before: 17
18</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Like the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='next'><code>next()</code></a> method,
it runs the generator code from where it started (on
the first call) or last yielded, stopping at the next
<code>yield</code> expression. It returns the
value of the <code>yield</code> expression.
It also sends the value <code>val</code> back to
the generator's <code>yield</code> expression.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='generator-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported Generator Operations</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li><code>a_gen.throw()</code></li><li><code>a_gen.close()</code></li></ul> </div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in Generators -->
</div> <!-- Closes Generators -->

<h3 id='Files'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>File Objects</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='a_file-read'><code>a_file.read</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='a_file-readline'><code>a_file.readline</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='a_file-readlines'><code>a_file.readlines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='urllib2-urlopen'><code>urllib2.urlopen</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='next'><code>an_iter.next</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Counter-elements'><code>a_counter.elements</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-in'><code>in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-not-in'><code>not in</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-len'><code>len</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sum'><code>sum</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-max'><code>max</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-min'><code>min</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-zip'><code>zip</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-sorted'><code>sorted</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-map'><code>map</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-filter'><code>filter</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='iter-reduce'><code>reduce</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='any'><code>any</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='all'><code>all</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='string-join'><code>a_str.join</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='enumerate'><code>enumerate</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&lt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>&gt;=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterators'>Iterators</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file2url'><code>codeskulptor.file2url</code></a> &mdash; Abbreviating standard URLs</dd> </dl>

<p>
This module contains functions for obtaining input data from
the web. Currently, CodeSkulptor's implementation of this
module supports input only, not output, and only from a
a CodeSkulptor-affiliated data storage site.
To use these operations, first import the module with
<code>import urllib2</code>.
</p>

<p>
<dfn>File objects</dfn> represent open files.
A file object keeps track of the current position in the file.
Each read operation gets data starting at this position
and advances the position to the end of the returned data.
CodeSkulptor only supports obtaining an open file via
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='urllib2-urlopen'><code>urllib2.urlopen()</code></a>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='a_file-read'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Read from File</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_file.read()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_file.read()</code></dd><dd><code>a_file.read(size)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.read()</pre></td><td><pre>This is line one.
This is line two.
This is line three.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.read(7)</pre></td><td><pre>This is</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-readline'><code>a_file.readline()</code></a> &mdash; Reads one line</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-readlines'><code>a_file.readlines()</code></a> &mdash; Reads multiple lines</dd> </dl>

<p>
With no argument or a negative <code>size</code> argument,
this returns a string containing
the rest of the file.
</p>

<p>
With a non-negative <code>size</code> argument, this
returns a string containing the next at-most
<code>size</code> bytes (characters) of the file.
It returns fewer bytes than requested only when there
are fewer bytes remaining in the file.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='a_file-readline'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Read One Line from File</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_file.readline()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_file.readline()</code></dd><dd><code>a_file.readline(size)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.readline()</pre></td><td><pre>This is line one.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.read(7)
print a_file.readline()</pre></td><td><pre>This is
line one.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-read'><code>a_file.read()</code></a> &mdash; Reads</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-readlines'><code>a_file.readlines()</code></a> &mdash; Reads multiple lines</dd> </dl>

<p>
With no argument or a negative <code>size</code> argument,
this returns a string containing
the rest of the current line in the file.
I.e., it returns all the characters up to and including
the next newline character <code>'\n'</code> or end of file.
</p>

<p>
With a non-negative <code>size</code> argument, this
returns a string containing the next at-most
<code>size</code> bytes (characters) of the file.
It returns fewer bytes than requested only when there
are fewer bytes remaining in the file.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='a_file-readlines'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Read Multiple Lines from File</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_file.readlines()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_file.readlines()</code></dd><dd><code>a_file.readlines(sizehint)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.readlines()</pre></td><td><pre>['This is line one.\n', 'This is line two.\n', 'This is line three.\n']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.readline()
print a_file.readlines()</pre></td><td><pre>This is line one.
['This is line two.\n', 'This is line three.\n']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-read'><code>a_file.read()</code></a> &mdash; Reads</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file-readline'><code>a_file.readline()</code></a> &mdash; Reads one line</dd> </dl>

<p>
Reads the rest of the file, separating its content into
a sequence of lines ending in the newline character
<code>'\n'</code>. This sequence is returned as a list
of strings.
</p>

<p>
The number <code>sizehint</code> is an estimate of how
many bytes remain in the file. Its value does not
affect the result.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='a_file-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported File Object Operations</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li><code>list()</code> on file objects</li><li><code>a_file.close()</code></li><li><code>a_file.fileno()</code></li><li><code>a_file.flush()</code></li><li><code>a_file.isatty()</code></li><li><code>a_file.seek()</code></li><li><code>a_file.tell()</code></li><li><code>a_file.truncate()</code></li><li><code>a_file.write()</code></li><li><code>a_file.writelines()</code></li><li><code>a_file.xreadlines()</code></li><li><code>a_file.closed</code></li><li><code>a_file.encoding</code></li><li><code>a_file.errors</code></li><li><code>a_file.mode</code></li><li><code>a_file.name</code></li><li><code>a_file.newlines</code></li><li><code>a_file.softspace</code></li></ul> </div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in file objects -->
</div> <!-- Closes file objects -->
