data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclasses:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Dictionaries'>Dictionaries</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterables'>Iterables</a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
A counter is a mapping from keys to integers.
These integers are traditionally used as counts,
but negative integers are also allowed.
When looking up a key that has not been previously
added to the counter, its value will be zero.
</p>

<p>
To use these Counters, first import the module
with <code>import collections</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Counter'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create a Counter</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>collections.Counter()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>collections.Counter()</code></dd><dd><code>collections.Counter(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

print collections.Counter({'a': 3, 'c': -1})</pre></td><td><pre>Counter({'a': 3, 'c': -1})</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

c = collections.Counter()
c['a'] += 1
print c['a']
print c['b']</pre></td><td><pre>1
0</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

c = collections.Counter({'a': 3, 'c': -1})
c['a'] += 1
print c['a']
print c['b']</pre></td><td><pre>4
0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Dictionaries'>Dictionaries</a> &mdash; Counters support almost all dictionary operations.</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='defaultdict'>Default dictionaries</a> &mdash; Counters are specialized to integral values.</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a new Counter, possibly initialized
with counts provided in the iterable <code>an_iter</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Counter-elements'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create Iterator of Counter Elements</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_counter.elements()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_counter.elements()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

c = collections.Counter({'a': 3, 'c': 8})
i = c.elements()
print i.next()
print i.next()</pre></td><td><pre>('a', 3)
('c', 8)</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Creates an
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Iterators'>iterator</a> whose elements are the key/value
pairs of the counter <code>a_counter</code>.
The iterator's elements will be in an arbitrary
implementation-specific order.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Counter-most-common'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>List of Most Common Elements in Counter</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_counter.most_common()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_counter.most_common()</code></dd><dd><code>a_counter.most_common(n)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

print collections.Counter({'a': 3, 'b': 5, 'c': 1, 'd': 3}).most_common()</pre></td><td><pre>[('b', 5), ('a', 3), ('d', 3), ('c', 1)]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

print collections.Counter({'a': 3, 'b': 5, 'c': 1, 'd': 3}).most_common(2)</pre></td><td><pre>[('b', 5), ('a', 3)]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a list of pairs of the counter
<code>a_counter</code>'s <code>n</code> most common keys
and corresponding values, listed in descending value order.
Keys with the same value are listed in arbitrary order.
If <code>n</code> is not specified, then all key-value
pairs are listed.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Counter-subtract'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Subtract Counts from Counter</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_counter.subtract()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_counter.subtract(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

c = collections.Counter({'a': 1, 'b': 2})
c.subtract({'a': 4, 'c': 3})
print c</pre></td><td><pre>Counter({'a': -3, 'b': 2, 'c': -3})</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Mutates counter <code>a_counter</code> by subtracting
each key's respective value in <code>an_iter</code>
from its value in <code>a_counter</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Counter-update'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Counts to Counter</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_counter.update()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_counter.update(an_iter)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import collections

c = collections.Counter({'a': 1, 'b': 2})
c.update({'a': 4, 'c': 3})
print c</pre></td><td><pre>Counter({'a': 5, 'b': 2, 'c': 3})</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Mutates counter <code>a_counter</code> by adding
each key's respective value in <code>an_iter</code>
from its value in <code>a_counter</code>.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='RE'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Regular Expression Module</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-findall'><code>re.findall</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-search'><code>re.search</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-match'><code>re.match</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-split'><code>re.split</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-IGNORECASE'><code>re.IGNORECASE</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='match-obj'><code>match_obj.group</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='match-obj'><code>match_obj.groups</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Documentation:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/library/re.html' target='_blank'>Python Standard Library: <code>re</code></a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
<p>
This module allows use of
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='re-constants'>regular expressions</a>,
also known as regexps.
To use these operations, first import the module
with <code>import re</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='re-constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Regular Expressions</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Most of the
<a href='http://docs.python.org/2/library/re.html#regular-expression-syntax' target='_blank'>Python regular expression</a> syntax is supported.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='re-findall'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Find All Occurrences of a Pattern</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>re.findall()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>re.findall(pattern, string)</code></dd><dd><code>re.findall(pattern, string, flags = val)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.findall(r'ZZZ', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>[]</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.findall(r'[a-z]*o[a-z]*', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>['brown', 'fox']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.findall('[a-z]*a[a-z]*', 'A stitch in time saves nine.', re.IGNORECASE)</pre></td><td><pre>['A', 'saves']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a list of all the matches of the regular
expression pattern in the given text string.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='re-search'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Find First Occurrence of a Pattern</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>re.search()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>re.search(pattern, string)</code></dd><dd><code>re.search(pattern, string, flags = val)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.search(r'ZZZ', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>None</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

if re.search(r'ZZZ', 'a quick brown fox'):
print 'Found pattern.'
else:
print 'Did not find pattern.'</pre></td><td><pre>Did not find pattern.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

m = re.search(r'[a-z]*o[a-z]*', 'a quick brown fox')
print m.group(0)</pre></td><td><pre>brown</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

m = re.search('[a-z]*a[a-z]*', 'A stitch in time saves nine.', re.IGNORECASE)
print m.group(0)</pre></td><td><pre>A</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the first match, if any, of the regular
expression pattern in the given text string.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='re-match'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Find First Occurrence of a Pattern at Beginning</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>re.match()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>re.search(pattern, string)</code></dd><dd><code>re.search(pattern, string, flags = val)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.match(r'ZZZ', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>None</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

if re.match(r'ZZZ', 'a quick brown fox'):
print 'Found pattern.'
else:
print 'Did not find pattern.'</pre></td><td><pre>Did not find pattern.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.match(r'[a-z]*o[a-z]*', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>None</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

m = re.match('[a-z]*a[a-z]*', 'A stitch in time saves nine.', re.IGNORECASE)
print m.group(0)</pre></td><td><pre>A</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the match, if any, of the regular
expression pattern at the beginning of the given text string.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='re-split'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Split on All Occurrences of a Pattern</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>re.split()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>re.split(pattern, string)</code></dd><dd><code>re.split(pattern, string, maxsplit = val)</code></dd><dd><code>re.split(pattern, string, maxsplit = val, flags = val)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.split(r'\s+', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'quick', 'brown', 'fox']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.split(r'\s+', 'a quick brown fox', 2)</pre></td><td><pre>['a', 'quick', 'brown fox']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.split(r'(\s+)', 'a quick brown fox')</pre></td><td><pre>['a', ' ', 'quick', ' ', 'brown', ' ', 'fox']</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import re

print re.split('a', 'A stitch in time saves nine.', 0, re.IGNORECASE)</pre></td><td><pre>['', ' stitch in time s', 'ves nine.']</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Splits the given text string into a list of strings,
using the pattern regular expression as separators.
If the regular expression is surrounded by parentheses,
then the instances of the separators are included
in the list of strings, otherwise they are not.
</p>

<p>
If <code>maxsplit</code> is positive, then
it splits the text at the first <code>maxsplit</code>
occurrences of the pattern.
If <code>flags</code> is positive, then the
pattern is modified by the flags.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='re-IGNORECASE'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Flag to Ignore Case</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>re.I</code>, <code>re.IGNORECASE</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>re.I</code></dd><dd><code>re.IGNORECASE</code></dd> </dl>

<p>
Flag to indicate that regular expression pattern
matching should be case-insensitive. By default,
matching is case sensitive.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='match-obj'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Groups of Match</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>match_obj.group()</code>, <code>match_obj.groups()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>match_obj.group(a_num)</code></dd><dd><code>match_obj.groups(a_num)</code></dd><dt>Documentation:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://docs.python.org/2/library/re.html#re.MatchObject' target='_blank'>Match Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
</div>
<h3 id='re-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported Regular Expression Module Operations</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li><code>re.compile()</code></li><li><code>re.finditer()</code></li><li><code>re.sub()</code></li><li><code>re.subn()</code></li><li><code>re.escape()</code></li><li><code>re.purge()</code></li><li><code>re.DEBUG</code></li><li><code>re.L</code></li><li><code>re.LOCALE</code></li><li><code>re.M</code></li><li><code>re.MULTILINE</code></li><li><code>re.S</code></li><li><code>re.DOTALL</code></li><li><code>re.U</code></li><li><code>re.UNICODE</code></li><li><code>re.X</code></li><li><code>re.VERBOSE</code></li><li><code>match_obj.expand()</code></li><li><code>match_obj.groupdict()</code></li><li><code>match_obj.start()</code></li><li><code>match_obj.end()</code></li><li><code>match_obj.span()</code></li><li><code>match_obj.pos</code></li><li><code>match_obj.endpos</code></li><li><code>match_obj.lastindex</code></li><li><code>match_obj.lastgroup</code></li><li><code>match_obj.re</code></li><li><code>match_obj.string</code></li></ul> </div>

<h3 id='Time'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Time Module</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operation:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='time-time'><code>time.time</code></a></li></ul></dd> </dl>
<p>
This module includes operations that measure the passage
of time.
To use these operations, first import the module with
<code>import time</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='time-time'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Current Time</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>time.time()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>time.time()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import time

print time.time()</pre></td><td><pre>1349712380.59 # One possible output.</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import time

time1 = time.time()
&hellip; # The code being timed
time2 = time.time()
print 'Time elapsed:', time2 - time1</pre></td><td><pre>Time elapsed: 2.64113 # One possible output.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>
<p>
Returns the current time as the number of
seconds since some constant system-defined time.
</p>

<p>
A common usage is to measure the time to run
an operation, as in the last example above.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='urllib2'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Urllib2 Module</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operation:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='urllib2-urlopen'><code>urllib2.urlopen</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Files'>File Objects</a> &mdash; Operations on opened files</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file2url'><code>codeskulptor.file2url</code></a> &mdash; Abbreviating standard URLs</dd> </dl>

<p>
This module contains functions for obtaining input data from
the web. Currently, CodeSkulptor's implementation of this
module supports input only, not output, and only from a
a CodeSkulptor-affiliated data storage site.
To use these operations, first import the module with
<code>import urllib2</code>.
</p>

<p>
<dfn>File objects</dfn> represent open files.
A file object keeps track of the current position in the file.
Each read operation gets data starting at this position
and advances the position to the end of the returned data.
CodeSkulptor only supports obtaining an open file via
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='urllib2-urlopen'><code>urllib2.urlopen()</code></a>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='urllib2-urlopen'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Open File at URL</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>urllib2.urlopen()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>urllib2.urlopen(url)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets_sample_text.txt'))
print a_file.read()</pre></td><td><pre>This is line one.
This is line two.
This is line three.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a read-only file object of the data found at
the given URL. Causes no error if there is no such URL.
</p>

<p>
Currently, the only URLs that are supported are those
files provided by the CodeSkulptor authors.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id='urllib2-unsupported'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Unsupported Urllib2 Module Operations</span></a></h3> <div>
<ul class='horiz-list'><li><code>urllib2.urlopen()</code> with multiple arguments</li><li><code>urllib2.install_opener()</code></li><li><code>urllib2.build_opener()</code></li></ul> </div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in urllib2 -->
</div> <!-- Closes urllib2 -->
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in tabs-StdModules -->
</div> <!-- Closes tabs-StdModules -->

<div id="tabs-Graphics">
<p>
<a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/' target='_blank'>CodeSkulptor</a> implements three custom modules for graphics in the browser,
each with an easy-to-learn interface.
The SimpleGUI module is for building interactive programs
and drawing.
The SimpleMap module is for drawing features on maps.
The SimplePlot module is for plotting numeric data.
To use these operations, first import the appropriate module with
<code>import simplegui</code>, <code>import simplemap</code>,
or <code>import simpleplot</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Frames'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Frame</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='simplegui-create_frame'><code>simplegui.create_frame</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-set_canvas_background'><code>frame.set_canvas_background</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-start'><code>frame.start</code></a></li><li><a href='#' data-dest='frame-add_label'><code>frame.add_label</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_button'><code>frame.add_button</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_input'><code>frame.add_input</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='keyboard-input'><code>frame.set_keydown_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='keyboard-input'><code>frame.set_keyup_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='mouse-input'><code>frame.set_mouseclick_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='mouse-input'><code>frame.set_mousedrag_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_draw_handler'><code>frame.set_draw_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2a_simplegui-frame.py' target='_blank'>Frames</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2a_simplegui-errors.py' target='_blank'>Common Errors with Frames</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
A frame is a window, which is a container for the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Controls'>controls</a>,
status information, and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Canvases'>canvas</a>.
A program can create only one frame.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='simplegui-create_frame'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create Frame</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplegui.create_frame()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplegui.create_frame(title, canvas_width, canvas_height)</code></dd><dd><code>simplegui.create_frame(title, canvas_width, canvas_height, control_width)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 200, 200, 300)</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Creates a new frame for interactive programs.
The frame's window has the given title, a string.
The frame consists of two parts: a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Controls'>control panel</a> on the left and a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Canvases'>canvas</a> on the right.
The control panel's width in pixels can be specified by
the number <code>control_width</code>.
The canvas width in pixels is the number
<code>canvas_width</code>.
The height in pixels of both the control panel and canvas
is the number <code>canvas_height</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='frame-set_canvas_background'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set Canvas' Background Color</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.set_canvas_background()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.set_canvas_background(color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_canvas_background('Red')
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with a red background</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Changes the background color of the frame's canvas,
which defaults to black.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='frame-start'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Start Frame's Interactivity</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.start()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.start()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Starts all frame event handlers &mdash; drawing and controls.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='frame-get_canvas_textwidth'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Canvas Text's Width</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.get_canvas_textwidth()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.get_canvas_textwidth(text, size)</code></dd><dd><code>frame.get_canvas_textwidth(text, size, face)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
print frame.get_canvas_textwidth('hello', 12)</pre></td><td><pre>23</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
print frame.get_canvas_textwidth('hello', 12, 'sans-serif')</pre></td><td><pre>27</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a text string, a font size, and a font face, this
returns the width of the text in pixels.
It does <em>not</em> draw the text.
This is useful in computing the position to draw text
when you want it centered or right justified in some
region.
</p>

<p>
The supported font faces are the default
<code>"serif"</code>,
<code>"sans-serif"</code>, and
<code>"monospace"</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Controls'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Control Objects</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_text'><code>control.get_text</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_text'><code>control.set_text</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_label'><code>frame.add_label</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_button'><code>frame.add_button</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_input'><code>frame.add_input</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='keyboard-input'><code>frame.set_keydown_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='keyboard-input'><code>frame.set_keyup_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='mouse-input'><code>frame.set_mousedrag_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
Control objects are placed in the control panel,
which is the left-hand part of the frame.
They are placed top-down in the order of creation.
Status information is at the bottom of the control panel.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='frame-add_label'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Text Label to Frame Control Panel</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.add_label()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.add_label(text)</code></dd><dd><code>frame.add_label(text, width)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
label1 = frame.add_label('My first label')
label2 = frame.add_label('My second label', 200)
label3 = frame.add_label('My third label', 20)</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with three labels</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_text'><code>control.get_text()</code></a> &mdash; Gets the current label text</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_text'><code>control.set_text()</code></a> &mdash; Sets the current label text</dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds a text label to the control panel.
The width of the label defaults to fit the width of
the given text, but can be specified in pixels.
If the provided width is less than that of the text,
the text overflows the label.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='frame-add_button'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Button to Frame Control Panel</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.add_button()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.add_button(text, button_handler)</code></dd><dd><code>frame.add_button(text, button_handler, width)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def button_handler():
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
button1 = frame.add_button('Label 1', button_handler)
button2 = frame.add_button('Label 2', button_handler, 50)</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with two buttons</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_buttons-structure.py' target='_blank'>Button Definitions</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_buttons-canvas_color.py' target='_blank'>Canvas Color</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_buttons-prize_boxes.py' target='_blank'>Prize Boxes</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_buttons-true_false_quiz.py' target='_blank'>True-False Quiz</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_text'><code>control.get_text()</code></a> &mdash; Gets the current label text</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_text'><code>control.set_text()</code></a> &mdash; Sets the current label text</dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds a button to the frame's control panel
with the given text label.
The width of the button defaults to fit the
given text, but can be specified in pixels.
If the provided width is less than that of the text, the
text overflows the button.
</p>

<p>
The handler should be defined with no parameters,
as in the above example.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='frame-add_input'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Text Input Box to Frame Control Panel</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.add_input()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.add_input(text, input_handler, width)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def input_handler(text_input):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
inp = frame.add_input('My label', input_handler, 50)</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with one input box</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_input_fields-structure.py' target='_blank'>Input Field Definitions</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_input_fields-functions.py' target='_blank'>Input Fields with Functions</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_input_fields-factoring.py' target='_blank'>Factoring</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-2b_input_fields-silly_words.py' target='_blank'>Silly Words</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3a_string_processing-input_checking.py' target='_blank'>Input Checking</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3a_string_processing-initials.py' target='_blank'>Initials</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_text'><code>control.get_text()</code></a> &mdash; Gets the current input text</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_text'><code>control.set_text()</code></a> &mdash; Sets the current input text, e.g., to specify a default value</dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds a text input field to the control panel with the
given text label.
The input field has the given width in pixels.
</p>

<p>
The handler should be defined with one parameter,
as in the above example. This parameter will receive
a string of the text input when the user presses
the <kbd>Enter</kbd> key.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='get_text'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get the Text of Control Object</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>control.get_text()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>control.get_text()</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
label = frame.add_label('Label')
label.set_text('New label')
print label.get_text()</pre></td><td><pre>New label</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def button_handler():
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
button = frame.add_button('Press this button', button_handler)
print button.get_text()</pre></td><td><pre>Press this button</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def input_handler(text_input):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
inp = frame.add_input('Label', input_handler, 50)
print inp.get_text()</pre></td><td><pre></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_text'><code>control.set_text()</code></a> &mdash; Sets the text</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the text in a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_label'>label</a>,
the text label of a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_button'>button</a>,
or the text in the input field of a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_input'>text input</a>,
respectively.
For an input field, this is useful to look at the contents
of the input field before the user presses the
<kbd>Enter</kbd> key.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='set_text'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set the Text of Control Object</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>control.set_text()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>control.set_text(text)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
label = frame.add_label('Label')
label.set_text('New label')</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with a text string</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def button_handler():
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
button = frame.add_button('Label', button_handler)
button.set_text('New label')</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with one button</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def input_handler(text_input):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
inp = frame.add_input('Label', input_handler, 50)
inp.set_text('Default contents')</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with one input box</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_text'><code>control.get_text()</code></a> &mdash; Gets the text</dd> </dl>

<p>
Changes the text in a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_label'>label</a>,
the text label of a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_button'>button</a>,
or the text in the input field of a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-add_input'>text input</a>,
respectively.
For a button, it also resizes the button if the button
wasn't created with a particular width.
For an input field, this is useful to provide a default input
for the input field.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='keyboard-input'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set the Keyboard Input Handler</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.set_keydown_handler()</code>,
<code>frame.set_keyup_handler()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.set_keydown_handler(key_handler)</code></dd><dd><code>frame.set_keyup_handler(key_handler)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def key_handler(key):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_keydown_handler(key_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with active keydown handler</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-keyboard-0.py' target='_blank'>Key Echo</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a_keyboard_input-shape_selection.py' target='_blank'>Shape Selection</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-keyboard-1.py' target='_blank'>Ball Positional Control</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-velocity_control.py' target='_blank'>Ball Velocity Control</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
These add keyboard event handlers waiting for keydown,
and keyup events, respectively.
When any key is pressed, the keydown handler is called
once. When any key is released, the keyup handler is
called once.
</p>

<p>
The handler for each should be defined with one parameter,
as in the above example. This parameter will receive
an integer representing a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Keys'>keyboard character</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='mouse-input'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set the Mouse Input Handler</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.set_mouseclick_handler()</code>,
<code>frame.set_mousedrag_handler()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.set_mouseclick_handler(mouse_handler)</code></dd><dd><code>frame.set_mousedrag_handler(mouse_handler)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def mouse_handler(position):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_mouseclick_handler(mouse_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with active mouseclick handler</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-mouse_input.py' target='_blank'>Moving Circle</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_mouseclick_handlers-ball_movement.py' target='_blank'>Ball Movement</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_mouseclick_handlers-click_lines.py' target='_blank'>Click Lines</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_mouseclick_handlers-tic_tac_toe.py' target='_blank'>Tic-Tac-Toe</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
These add keyboard event handlers waiting for
mouseclick and mousedrag events, respectively.
When a mouse button is clicked, i.e., pressed and
released, the mouseclick handler is called once.
When a mouse is dragged while the mouse button is
being pressed, the mousedrag handler is called for
each new mouse position.
</p>

<p>
The handler for each should be defined with one parameter,
as in the above example. This parameter will receive
a pair of screen coordinates, i.e.,
a tuple of two non-negative integers.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in Control Objects -->
</div> <!-- Closes Control Objects -->

<h3 id='Canvases'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Canvas</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_text'><code>canvas.draw_text</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_line'><code>canvas.draw_line</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_polyline'><code>canvas.draw_polyline</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_polygon'><code>canvas.draw_polygon</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_circle'><code>canvas.draw_circle</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_point'><code>canvas.draw_point</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_image'><code>canvas.draw_image</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_draw_handler'><code>frame.set_draw_handler</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3a_canvas_and_drawing-structure.py'
