target='_blank'>Digital Numbers</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4b_velocity_control-ball_track.py' target='_blank'>Ball Track</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The canvas is where you can draw text and shapes.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='set_draw_handler'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set the Draw Handler on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>frame.set_draw_handler()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
&hellip;

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame with active draw handler</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds an event handler that is responsible for all drawing.
</p>

<p>
The handler should be defined with one parameter,
as in the above example. This parameter will receive a
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Canvases'>canvas object</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_text'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Text on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_text()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_text(text, point, font_size, font_color)</code></dd><dd><code>canvas.draw_text(text, point, font_size, font_color, font_face)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_text('A', (20, 20), 12, 'Red')
canvas.draw_text('B', [30, 50], 20, 'Blue')
canvas.draw_text('C', (80, 50), 12, 'Gray', 'serif')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws three letters</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Writes the given text string in the given font size, color,
and font face.
The point is a 2-element tuple or list of screen
coordinates representing the
lower-left-hand corner of where to write the text.
</p>

<p>
The supported font faces are
<code>"serif"</code> (the default),
<code>"sans-serif"</code>, and
<code>"monospace"</code>.
</p>

<p>
In order to position the text where you want, you may
want to determine the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='frame-get_canvas_textwidth'>text's width</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_line'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Line Segment on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_line()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_line(point1, point2, line_width, line_color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_line((10, 20), (30, 40), 12, 'Red')
canvas.draw_line([10, 20], [80, 70], 20, 'Blue')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws two lines</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-4a-motion-drawing_vectors.py' target='_blank'>Drawing Vectors</a></li></ul></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a line segment between the two points, each of
which is a 2-element tuple or list of screen coordinates.
The line's width is given in pixels and must be positive.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_polyline'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Connected Line Segments on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_polyline()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_polyline(point_list, line_width, line_color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_polyline([(10, 20), (30, 20), (90, 70)], 12, 'Red')
canvas.draw_polyline([[40, 20], [80, 40], [30, 90]], 20, 'Blue')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws two polylines</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a sequence of line segments between each adjacent
pair of points in the non-empty list.
It is an error for the list of points to be empty.
Each point is a
2-element tuple or list of screen coordinates.
The line's width is given in pixels and must be positive.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_polygon'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Polygon on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_polygon()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_polygon(point_list, line_width, line_color)</code></dd><dd><code>canvas.draw_polygon(point_list, line_width, line_color, fill_color = color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_polygon([(10, 20), (20, 30), (30, 10)], 12, 'Green')
canvas.draw_polygon([[30, 20], [40, 40], [50, 20], [10, 10]], 12, 'Red')
canvas.draw_polygon([(50, 70), (80, 40), (30, 90)], 5, 'Blue', 'White')
canvas.draw_polygon([[90, 70], [80, 40], [70, 90], [70, 70]], 12, 'Yellow', 'Orange')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws four polygons</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a sequence of line segments between each adjacent
pair of points in the non-empty list,
plus a line segment between the
first and last points.
It is an error for the list of points to be empty.
Each point is a
2-element tuple or list of screen coordinates.
The line's width is given in pixels, and must be positive.
The fill color defaults to <code>None</code>.
If the fill color is specified, then the interior
of the polygon is colored.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_circle'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Circle on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_circle()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_circle(center_point, radius, line_width, line_color)</code></dd><dd><code>canvas.draw_circle(center_point, radius, line_width, line_color, fill_color = color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_circle((10, 10), 20, 12, 'Green')
canvas.draw_circle([20, 30], 30, 12, 'Red')
canvas.draw_circle((50, 50), 20, 5, 'Blue', 'White')
canvas.draw_circle([70, 80], 30, 10, 'Yellow', 'Orange')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws four circles</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a circle at the given center point having
the given radius.
The point is a 2-element tuple or list of screen coordinates.
The line's width is given in pixels and must be positive.
The fill color defaults to <code>None</code>.
If the fill color is specified, then the interior
of the circle is colored.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_point'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Point on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_point()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_point(point, color)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_point((10, 10), 'Green')
canvas.draw_point([20, 30], 'Red')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws two points</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Colors'>Colors</a> &mdash; Supported colors</dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a 1&times;1 rectangle at the given point in the
given color.
The point is a 2-element tuple or list of screen coordinates.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='draw_image'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Image on Canvas</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>canvas.draw_image()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>canvas.draw_image(image, center_source, width_height_source, center_dest, width_height_dest)</code></dd><dd><code>canvas.draw_image(image, center_source, width_height_source, center_dest, width_height_dest, rotation)</code></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_image(image, (1521 / 2, 1818 / 2), (1521, 1818), (50, 50), (100, 100))

image = simplegui.load_image('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/gutenberg.jpg')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws a scaled map</pre></td></tr><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_image(image, (1521 // 2, 1818 // 2), (1521, 1818), (40, 70), (100, 100), 2)

image = simplegui.load_image('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/gutenberg.jpg')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws a strangely rotated scaled map</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Draw an image that was previously
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_image'>loaded</a>.
<code>center_source</code> is a pair of coordinates giving
the position of the center of the image, while
<code>center_dest</code> is a pair of screen coordinates
specifying where the center of the image should be drawn on
the canvas.
<code>width_height_source</code> is a pair of integers giving
the size of the original image, while
<code>width_height_dest</code> is a pair of integers giving
the size of how the images should be drawn.
The image can be rotated clockwise by <code>rotation</code>
radians.
</p>

<p>
You can draw the whole image file or just part of it.
The source information (<code>center_source</code>
and <code>width_height_source</code>) specifies which
pixels to display. If it attempts to use
any pixels outside of the actual file size, then no
image will be drawn.
</p>

<p>
Specifying
a different width or height in the destination than in
the source will rescale the image.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='Timers'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Timers</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='create_timer'><code>simplegui.create_timer</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-start'><code>timer.start</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-stop'><code>timer.stop</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-is_running'><code>timer.is_running</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-timers.py' target='_blank'>Screensaver</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3b_timers-blinking_text.py' target='_blank'>Blinking Text</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-3b_timers-reaction_time.py' target='_blank'>Reaction Time</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-motion_explicit.py' target='_blank'>Timer-driven Ball Motion</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
A timer calls an event handler repeatedly at a specified
interval.
</p>

<p>
A program can have an arbitrary number of timers running
simultaneously.
However, having many timers running will slow CodeSkulptor.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='create_timer'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create Timer</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplegui.create_timer()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplegui.create_timer(interval, timer_handler)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def timer_handler():
&hellip;

timer = simplegui.create_timer(500, timer_handler)
timer.start()</pre></td><td><pre># starts a timer</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Creates a timer. Once
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-start'>started</a>,
it will repeatedly call the given
event handler at the specified interval, which is given
in milliseconds.
</p>

<p>
The handler should be defined with no arguments,
as in the above example.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='timer-start'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Start Timer</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>timer.start()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>timer.start()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def timer_handler():
&hellip;

timer = simplegui.create_timer(500, timer_handler)
timer.start()</pre></td><td><pre># starts a timer</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Starts or restarts the timer.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='timer-stop'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Stop Timer</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>timer.stop()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>timer.stop()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def timer_handler():
timer.stop()

timer = simplegui.create_timer(500, timer_handler)
timer.start()</pre></td><td><pre># starts a timer and stops it on its first tick</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Stops the timer. It can be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-start'>restarted</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='timer-is_running'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Check if Timer is Running</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>timer.is_running()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>timer.is_running()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def timer_handler():
pass

timer = simplegui.create_timer(100, timer_handler)
print timer.is_running()
timer.start()
print timer.is_running()
timer.stop()
print timer.is_running()</pre></td><td><pre>False
True
False</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns whether the timer is running, i.e.,
it has been
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-start'>started</a>,
but not
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='timer-stop'>stopped</a>.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='Images'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Images</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_image'><code>simplegui.load_image</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_width'><code>image.get_width</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='get_height'><code>image.get_height</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_image'><code>canvas.draw_image</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd><dt>Examples:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-images.py' target='_blank'>Map Magnifier</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_images-backgrounds.py' target='_blank'>Image Backgrounds</a></li><li><a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/#examples-more-5_images-changes.py' target='_blank'>Image Changes</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
An image must be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_image'>loaded</a> before it can be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='draw_image'>drawn</a>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='load_image'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Load Image</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplegui.load_image()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplegui.load_image(URL)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

def draw_handler(canvas):
canvas.draw_image(image, (1521 / 2, 1818 / 2), (1521, 1818), (50, 50), (100, 100))

image = simplegui.load_image('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/gutenberg.jpg')

frame = simplegui.create_frame('Testing', 100, 100)
frame.set_draw_handler(draw_handler)
frame.start()</pre></td><td><pre># Opens frame and draws a scaled map</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Loads an image from the specified URL.
The image can be in any format supported by the browser.
No error is raised if the file isn't found or is of
an unsupported format.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='get_width'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Image's Width</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>image.get_width()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>image.get_width()</code></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the width of the image in pixels.
While the image is still loading, it returns zero.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='get_height'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Image's Height</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>image.get_height()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>image.get_height()</code></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the height of the image in pixels.
While the image is still loading, it returns zero.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='Sounds'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Sounds</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_sound'><code>simplegui.load_sound</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-play'><code>sound.play</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-pause'><code>sound.pause</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-rewind'><code>sound.rewind</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set_volume'><code>sound.set_volume</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
A sound must be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_sound'>loaded</a> before it can be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-play'>played</a>.
To restart playing a sound from the beginning, it must first be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-rewind'>rewound</a>.
Separate sounds are played in separate audio channels and may
overlap.
The number of sounds that can be played simultaneously is
system-dependent.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='load_sound'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Load Sound</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplegui.load_sound()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplegui.load_sound(URL)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

sound = simplegui.load_sound('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/Epoq-Lepidoptera.ogg')
sound.set_volume(0.7)</pre></td><td><pre></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-play'><code>sound.play()</code></a> &mdash; How to play the sound</dd> </dl>

<p>
Loads a sound from the specified URL.
Supports whatever audio formats that your
<a href='https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/HTML/Supported_media_formats' target='_blank'>browser supports</a>.
No error is raised if the file isn't found or is of
an unsupported format.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='sound-play'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Play Sound</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>sound.play()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>sound.play()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

sound = simplegui.load_sound('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/Epoq-Lepidoptera.ogg')
sound.play()</pre></td><td><pre># plays a sound</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Starts playing a sound, or restarts playing it at the
point it was
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-pause'>paused</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='sound-pause'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Pause Sound</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>sound.pause()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>sound.pause()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

sound = simplegui.load_sound('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/Epoq-Lepidoptera.ogg')
sound.play()
sound.pause()</pre></td><td><pre># starts to play a sound, then immediate pauses</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Stops the playing of the sound. Playing can be restarted
at the stopped point with
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-play'><code>sound.play()</code></a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='sound-rewind'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Rewind Sound</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>sound.rewind()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>sound.rewind()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

sound = simplegui.load_sound('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/Epoq-Lepidoptera.ogg')
sound.play()
sound.rewind()
sound.play()</pre></td><td><pre></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Stops the playing of the sound, and makes it so the next
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='sound-play'><code>sound.play()</code></a> will start playing the sound at the beginning.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='set_volume'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set Sound's Volume</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>sound.set_volume()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>sound.set_volume(volume)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

sound = simplegui.load_sound('http://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/codeskulptor-assets/Epoq-Lepidoptera.ogg')
sound.set_volume(0.7)</pre></td><td><pre></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Changes the volume for the sound to be the given level
on a 0 (silent)&ndash;1.0 (maximum) scale.
Default is 1.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes Sounds accordion -->
</div> <!-- Closes Sounds -->

<h3 id='Constants'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleGUI Module &mdash; Constants</span></a></h3> <div>
<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Colors'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Color Constants</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
The following color names are considered the most standard.
</p>
<table class='list'><tr><th><code>'Aqua'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Aqua;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Black'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Black;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Blue'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Blue;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Fuchsia'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Fuchsia;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Gray'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Gray;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Green'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Green;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Lime'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Lime;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Maroon'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Maroon;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Navy'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Navy;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Olive'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Olive;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Orange'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Orange;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Purple'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Purple;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Red'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Red;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Silver'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Silver;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Teal'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Teal;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'White'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: White;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr><tr><th><code>'Yellow'</code></th><td><span style='background-color: Yellow;'>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;</span></td></tr></table> <p>
More generally, you may use any
<a href='http://www.w3schools.com/html/html_colornames.asp' target='_blank'>HTML color name</a>.
Furthermore, custom colors and transparencies can be
specified in a any
<a href='http://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_colors_legal.asp' target='_blank'>CSS color</a> format, including hexadecimal, RGB, RGBA, HSL, and HSLA.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='Keys'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Keyboard Character Constants</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplegui.KEY_MAP[]</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplegui.KEY_MAP[character]</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplegui

print simplegui.KEY_MAP['left']</pre></td><td><pre>37</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
The
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='keyboard-input'>keyboard event handlers</a> receive the relevant key
as an integer. Because different browsers can give
different values for the same keystrokes, SimpleGUI
provides a way to get the appropriate key integer for
a given meaning.
</p>

<p>
The acceptable strings for <code>character</code>
are the letters <code>'a'</code>&hellip;<code>'z'</code>
and <code>'A'</code>&hellip;<code>'Z'</code>,
the digits <code>'0'</code>&hellip;<code>'9'</code>,
<code>'space'</code>, <code>'left'</code>,
<code>'right'</code>, <code>'up'</code>,
and <code>'down'</code>.
Note that other keyboard symbols are not defined
in <code>simplegui.KEY_MAP</code>.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='Maps'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleMap Module &mdash; Maps</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='simplemap-create_map'><code>simplemap.create_map</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-add_marker'><code>a_map.add_marker</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-draw_line'><code>a_map.draw_line</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-get_markers'><code>a_map.get_markers</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-get_lines'><code>a_map.get_lines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear_markers'><code>a_map.clear_markers</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear_lines'><code>a_map.clear_lines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear'><code>a_map.clear</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-add_button'><code>a_map.add_button</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-add_break'><code>a_map.add_break</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The SimpleMap module provides an interface for drawing
and annotating maps. The underlying maps are provided by
Google Maps. Points on the map are referred to by
a pair of numbers representing
<a href='http://www.mapcoordinates.net/en' target='_blank'>latitude and longitude</a>.
</p>

<p>
The module uses three types of objects:
maps,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>markers</a>,
and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lines'>lines</a>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='simplemap-create_map'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simplemap.create_map()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simplemap.create_map(title, coordinates, map_width, map_height)</code></dd><dd><code>simplemap.create_map(title, coordinates, map_width, map_height, control_width)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)</pre></td><td><pre># Creates a map.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Creates a map in a new window titled by the string
<code>title</code> and with the given width and height
in pixels. The map contents are centered on the given
coordinates in
<a href='http://www.mapcoordinates.net/en' target='_blank'>latitude and longitude</a>.
</p>

<p>
If a <code>control_width</code> is given, it also creates
an control panel.
By default, no area is created, and such button controls are
not allowed.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-add_marker'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Marker to Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.add_marker()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.add_marker(description, id, icon_url, coordinates, handler)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)</pre></td><td><pre># Creates a map with one marker.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a marker on the map, adds a corresponding
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>marker object</a> to the map object, and returns the marker object.
The marker is represented
graphically by the image found at the URL string
<code>icon_url</code>. The marker is placed at the
<a href='http://www.mapcoordinates.net/en' target='_blank'>latitude and longitude</a> specified by the pair of numbers <code>coordinates</code>.
The marker has a <code>description</code> string which
appears when you hover the mouse on the marker.
The marker also has an <code>id</code> data string.
When the image is clicked on, the event
handler function <code>click_handler</code> will be called.
</p>

<p>
The handler should be defined with one parameter,
as in the above example. This parameter will receive the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>marker object</a> whose image was clicked on.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-draw_line'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Draw Line on Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.draw_line()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.draw_line(start_marker, stop_marker)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
wiess_college = rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
duncan_hall = rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

rice.draw_line(wiess_college, duncan_hall)</pre></td><td><pre># Draws a line between two map markers</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Draws a black path between the two given markers
on the map. The path follows the available streets.
Adds a corresponding
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lines'>line object</a> to the map object, and returns the line object.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-get_markers'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Set of all Markers on Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.get_markers()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.get_markers()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

for marker in rice.get_markers():
print marker.get_description()</pre></td><td><pre>Wiess College
Duncan Hall</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a set of all
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>marker objects</a> represented on the map.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-get_lines'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Set of all Lines on Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.get_lines()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>map.get_lines()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
wiess_college = rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
duncan_hall = rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

rice.draw_line(wiess_college, duncan_hall)

for line in rice.get_lines():
print line.get_start().get_description()
print line.get_stop().get_description()</pre></td><td><pre>Wiess College
Duncan Hall</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a set of all
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lines'>line objects</a> represented on the map.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-clear_markers'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Clear all Markers from Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.clear_markers()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.clear_markers()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
wiess_college = rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
duncan_hall = rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

rice.draw_line(wiess_college, duncan_hall)

rice.clear_markers()

print rice.get_markers()</pre></td><td><pre>set([])</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear'><code>map.clear()</code></a> &mdash; Removes all markers and lines</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='marker-remove'><code>marker.remove()</code></a> &mdash; Removes one marker</dd> </dl>

<p>
Erases all markers from the drawn map.
Does not remove any lines between those markers.
Removes all
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>marker objects</a> from the map object.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-clear_lines'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Clear all Lines from Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.clear_lines()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.clear_lines()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
wiess_college = rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
duncan_hall = rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

rice.draw_line(wiess_college, duncan_hall)

rice.clear_lines()

print rice.get_lines()</pre></td><td><pre>set([])</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear'><code>map.clear()</code></a> &mdash; Removes all markers and lines</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='line-remove'><code>a_line.remove()</code></a> &mdash; Removes one line</dd> </dl>

<p>
Erases all paths from the drawn map.
Does not remove any markers.
Removes all
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lines'>line objects</a> from the map object.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-clear'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Clear Everything from Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.clear()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.clear()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'
red_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_red.png'

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500)
wiess_college = rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)
duncan_hall = rice.add_marker('Duncan Hall', 'D', red_icon, (29.719887, -95.398617), click_handler)

rice.draw_line(wiess_college, duncan_hall)

rice.clear()

print rice.get_markers()
print rice.get_lines()</pre></td><td><pre>set([])
set([])</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear_markers'><code>map.clear_markers()</code></a> &mdash; Removes all markers</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear_lines'><code>map.clear_lines()</code></a> &mdash; Removes all lines</dd> </dl>

<p>
Erases all markers and line segments from the drawn map.
Removes all
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>marker objects</a> and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Lines'>line objects</a> from the map object.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-add_button'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Button Control to Map</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.add_button()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.add_button(text, handler)</code></dd><dd><code>a_map.add_button(text, handler, width)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500, 150)

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'

rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)

def delete_wiess ():
rice.clear_markers()
rice.add_button('Delete Wiess Marker', delete_wiess)</pre></td><td><pre># Creates map with button that will delete a marker</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds a button in the map's control panel
with the given text label.
The width of the button defaults to the width of the
given text, but can be specified in pixels.
If the provided width is less than that of the text, the
text overflows the button.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='map-add_break'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Add Line Break to Map Control Panel</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_map.add_button()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_map.add_break()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simplemap

rice = simplemap.create_map('Rice University', (29.716467, -95.404213), 500, 500, 150)

def click_handler(a_marker):
print 'Clicked on marker', a_marker.get_description()

green_icon = 'http://labs.google.com/ridefinder/images/mm_20_green.png'

rice.add_marker('Wiess College', 'W', green_icon, (29.714967, -95.400694), click_handler)

def delete_wiess ():
rice.clear_markers()
rice.add_button('Delete Wiess Marker', delete_wiess)
rice.add_break()
rice.add_button('Delete Wiess Marker', delete_wiess)</pre></td><td><pre># Creates map with two buttons that will delete a marker</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds a line break to the map's control panel.
Useful to separate buttons.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes SimpleMap Maps accordion -->
</div> <!-- Closes SimpleMap Maps -->

on the map. Its location is determined by a pair of

<h3 id='Lines'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimpleMap Module &mdash; Lines</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='line-get_start'><code>a_line.get_start</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='line-get_stop'><code>a_line.get_stop</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='line-set_color'><code>a_line.set_color</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='line-remove'><code>a_line.remove</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-draw_line'><code>a_map.draw_line</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-get_lines'><code>a_map.get_lines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear_lines'><code>a_map.clear_lines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='map-clear'><code>a_map.clear</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
A line object corresponds to a drawn path between two
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Markers'>markers</a> on the map. The path follows the available streets on the map.
The path color defaults to black.
</p>

<div class="accordion">

<h3 id='simpleplot'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>SimplePlot Module</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='plot-lines'><code>simpleplot.plot_lines</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='plot-bars'><code>simpleplot.plot_bars</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='plot-scatter'><code>simpleplot.plot_scatter</code></a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
SimplePlot provides functions for plotting numeric data
&mdash; both the x- and y-coordinate values should be numbers.
To use its operations, first import the module with
<code>import simpleplot</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='plot-lines'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Make Line Plot</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simpleplot.plot_lines()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_lines(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets)</code></dd><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_lines(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets, points)</code></dd><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_lines(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets, points, legends)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simpleplot

dataset1 = {3: 5, 8: 2, 1: 3}
dataset2 = [(1, 2), (4, 7), (2, 5), (7, 6)]
simpleplot.plot_lines('Sample', 400, 300, 'x', 'y', [dataset1, dataset2], True, ['dataset1', 'dataset2'])</pre></td><td><pre># pops up a line plot</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Displays a plot in a new window named <code>framename</code>
with the <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> given
in pixels.
The x-axis is labeled with the string <code>xlabel</code>.
The y-axis is labeled with the string <code>ylabel</code>.
</p>

<p>
The data to display is given in <code>datasets</code>, which
is a sequence of data sets. Each data set is connected
with a line through each data point.
Each data set can be given in either of two representations.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
A data set can be a sequence of 2-element sequences,
where a 2-element sequence represents an x,y-pair.
This allows for multiple points to have the same x value.
Points are displayed in the given order.
</li>
<li>
A data set can also be a dictionary mapping each
x value to a corresponding y value.
Points are displayed in order of x value.
</li>
</ul>

<p>
The optional boolean <code>points</code> indicates
that the individual points should be indicated. It defaults
to <code>False</code>.
</p>

<p>
The optional <code>legends</code> is a sequence of strings
that label the data sets and will be displayed in a legend.
If omitted, there will be no legend.
The length of this sequence should be the same as the length
of <code>datasets</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='plot-bars'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Make Bar Plot</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simpleplot.plot_bars()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_bars(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets)</code></dd><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_bars(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets, legends)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simpleplot

dataset1 = {3: 5, 8: 2, 1: 3}
dataset2 = [(1, 2), (4, 7), (2, 5), (7, 6)]
simpleplot.plot_bars('Sample', 400, 300, 'x', 'y', [dataset1, dataset2], ['dataset1', 'dataset2'])</pre></td><td><pre># pops up a bar plot</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Displays a plot in a new window named <code>framename</code>
with the <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> given
in pixels.
The x-axis is labeled with the string <code>xlabel</code>.
The y-axis is labeled with the string <code>ylabel</code>.
</p>

<p>
The data to display is given in <code>datasets</code>, which
is a sequence of data sets. Each data point is represented
by a vertical bar, and corresponding data points of each
data set are grouped together.
Each data set can be given in either of two representations.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
A data set can be a sequence of 2-element sequences,
where a 2-element sequence represents an x,y-pair.
This allows for multiple points to have the same x value.
Points are displayed in the given order.
</li>
<li>
A data set can also be a dictionary mapping each
x value to a corresponding y value.
Points are displayed in order of x value.
</li>
</ul>

<p>
The optional <code>legends</code> is a sequence of strings
that label the data sets and will be displayed in a legend.
If omitted, there will be no legend.
The length of this sequence should be the same as the length
of <code>datasets</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='plot-scatter'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Make Scatter Plot</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>simpleplot.plot_scatter()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_scatter(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets)</code></dd><dd><code>simpleplot.plot_scatter(framename, width, height, xlabel, ylabel, datasets, legends)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import simpleplot

dataset1 = {3: 5, 8: 2, 1: 3}
dataset2 = [(1, 2), (4, 7), (1, 5), (2, 5), (4, 3), (7, 6)]
simpleplot.plot_scatter('Sample', 400, 300, 'x', 'y', [dataset1, dataset2], ['dataset1', 'dataset2'])</pre></td><td><pre># pops up a scatter plot</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Displays a plot in a new window named <code>framename</code>
with the <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> given
in pixels.
The x-axis is labeled with the string <code>xlabel</code>.
The y-axis is labeled with the string <code>ylabel</code>.
</p>

<p>
The data to display is given in <code>datasets</code>, which
is a sequence of data sets. Each data point is represented
by a colored dot, and corresponding data points of each
data set are the same color.
Each data set can be given in either of two representations.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
A data set can be a sequence of 2-element sequences,
where a 2-element sequence represents an x,y-pair.
This allows for multiple points to have the same x value.
Points are displayed in the given order.
</li>
<li>
A data set can also be a dictionary mapping each
x value to a corresponding y value.
</li>
</ul>

<p>
The optional <code>legends</code> is a sequence of strings
that label the data sets and will be displayed in a legend.
If omitted, there will be no legend.
The length of this sequence should be the same as the length
of <code>datasets</code>.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="tabs-Other">
<p>
<a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/' target='_blank'>CodeSkulptor</a> implements two other custom modules.
The Numeric module is for mathematics with two-dimensional matrices.
The CodeSkulptor module is a small collection of miscellaneous
operations.
To use these operations, first import the appropriate module with
<code>import numeric</code> or <code>import codeskulptor</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='Matrices'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Numeric Module &mdash; Matrices</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-Matrix'><code>numeric.Matrix</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-subtract'><code>-</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-multiply'><code>*</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-inverse'><code>a_matrix.inverse</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-transpose'><code>a_matrix.transpose</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-abs'><code>a_matrix.abs</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-summation'><code>a_matrix.summation</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='numeric-shape'><code>a_matrix.shape</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>==</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>!=</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='op-comparison'><code>is not</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='type'><code>type</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='isinstance'><code>isinstance</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='dir'><code>dir</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='hasattr'><code>hasattr</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='str'><code>str</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='repr'><code>repr</code></a></li></ul></dd><dt>Superclass:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='Objects'>Objects</a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The Numeric module is for mathematics with two-dimensional
matrices. It provides some of the basic operations of
linear algebra.
Matrices are restricted to only contain numbers.
This module is not a part of standard Python,
rather it is a smaller module than the common NumPy module.
To use these operations, first import the module with
<code>import numeric</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='numeric-Matrix'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create a Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>numeric.Matrix()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>numeric.Matrix(data)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print numeric.Matrix([[0, 1], [3, 7], [5, 2]])</pre></td><td><pre>[[0, 1],
[3, 7],
[5, 2]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a 2-dimensional matrix object corresponding to the
given data, which must be a sequence of sequences.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-identity'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Create an Identity Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>numeric.identity()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>numeric.identity(size)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print numeric.identity(3)</pre></td><td><pre>[[1, 0, 0],
[0, 1, 0],
[0, 0, 1]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a <code>size</code>&times;<code>size</code>
2-dimensional identity matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-__getitem__'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get Matrix Value at Specified Indices</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix[]</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix[(i, j)]</code></dd><dd><code>a_matrix.__getitem__((i, j))</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print numeric.identity(3)[(0, 0)]</pre></td><td><pre>1.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns the value in the matrix <code>a_matrix</code> at
row <code>i</code> and column <code>j</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-getrow'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get One Row of Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.getrow()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.getrow(i)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print numeric.identity(3).getrow(1)</pre></td><td><pre>[[0, 1, 0]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
If the given matrix <code>a_matrix</code> has dimensions
<var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var>, then the result is a new
1&times;<var>n</var> matrix that is a copy of
row <code>i</code> of the matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-getcol'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get One Column of Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.getcol()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.getcol(j)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print numeric.identity(3).getcol(2)</pre></td><td><pre>[[0, 0, 1]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
If the given matrix <code>a_matrix</code> has dimensions
<var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var>, then the result is a new
1&times;<var>m</var> matrix that is a copy of
column <code>j</code> of the matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-__setitem__'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set Matrix Value at Specified Indices</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix[]=</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix[(i, j)] = value</code></dd><dd><code>a_matrix.__setitem__((i, j), value)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.identity(3)
matrix[(0, 0)] = 5
print matrix</pre></td><td><pre>[[5, 0, 0],
[0, 1, 0],
[0, 0, 1]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Sets the value in the matrix <code>a_matrix</code> at
row <code>i</code> and column <code>j</code> to be
value <code>value</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-add'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Matrix Addition</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>+</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>matrix1 + matrix2</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.identity(3)
print matrix + matrix</pre></td><td><pre>[[2, 0, 0],
[0, 2, 0],
[0, 0, 2]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Adds two <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrices.
The result is a new <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-subtract'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Matrix Subtraction</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>-</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>matrix1 - matrix2</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.identity(3)
print matrix - matrix</pre></td><td><pre>[[0, 0, 0],
[0, 0, 0],
[0, 0, 0]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Subtracts <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix
<code>matrix2</code> from <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var>
matrix <code>matrix1</code>.
The result is a new <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-multiply'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Matrix Multiplication</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>*</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>matrix1 * matrix2</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix1 = numeric.Matrix([[1, 2]])
matrix2 = numeric.Matrix([[3, 4, 5], [6, 7, 8]])
print matrix1 * matrix2</pre></td><td><pre>[[15, 18, 21]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Muliplies <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix
<code>matrix1</code> by <var>n</var>&times;<var>p</var>
matrix <code>matrix2</code>.
The result is a new <var>m</var>&times;<var>p</var> matrix.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-scale'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Matrix Multiplication by a Number</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.scale()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.scale(factor)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.Matrix([[3, 4, 5], [6, 7, 8]])
print matrix.scale(2)</pre></td><td><pre>[[[6, 8, 10],
[12, 14, 16]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix and
a number <code>factor</code>, it returns a new
<var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix where
each original element has been multiplied by
<code>factor</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-copy'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Copy Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.copy()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.copy()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix1 = numeric.Matrix([[1, 2]])
matrix2 = matrix1.copy()
matrix2[(0, 0)] = 5
print matrix1</pre></td><td><pre>[[1, 2]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Makes a new matrix with the same elements as
<code>a_matrix</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-inverse'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Invert Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.inverse()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.inverse()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.Matrix([[1, 0], [1, 2]])
print matrix.inverse()</pre></td><td><pre>[[1, 0],
[-0.5, -0.5]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a <var>n</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix
<code>a_matrix</code>, it returns its
<var>n</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix inverse,
if it exists.
Inverses exist only for some square matrices.
If no inverse exists, an error is raised.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-transpose'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Transpose Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.transpose()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.transpose()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.Matrix([[1, 2]])
print matrix.transpose()</pre></td><td><pre>[[1],
[2]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix
<code>a_matrix</code>, it returns its
<var>n</var>&times;<var>m</var> matrix transpose.
I.e., if a value is in the original matrix at row
<var>i</var> and column <var>j</var>, then it is
at row <var>j</var> and column <var>i</var> in its transpose.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-abs'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Absolute Value of Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.abs()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.abs()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

matrix = numeric.Matrix([[1, -2, -5]])
print matrix.abs()</pre></td><td><pre>[[1, 2, 5]]</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
Given a <var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix
<code>a_matrix</code>, it returns a new
<var>m</var>&times;<var>n</var> matrix consisting of the
absolute values of each of the original elements.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-summation'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Sum Elements in Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.summation()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.summation()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

print matrix.summation()</pre></td><td><pre>-4.0</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

Returns the sum of all the elements in the matrix
<code>a_matrix</code>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='numeric-shape'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Shape of Matrix</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>a_matrix.shape()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>a_matrix.shape()</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import numeric

<h3 id='CodeSkulptor'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Module</span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Operations:</dt><dd><ul class='horiz-list'><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='set-timeout'><code>codeskulptor.set_timeout</code></a></li><li><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='file2url'><code>codeskulptor.file2url</code></a></li></ul></dd> </dl>

<p>
The CodeSkulptor module is a small collection of miscellaneous
operations that are not in standard Python.
To use these operations, first import the module with
<code>import codeskulptor</code>.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='set-timeout'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Set CodeSkulptor's Timeout Limit</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>codeskulptor.set_timeout()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>codeskulptor.set_timeout(seconds)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import codeskulptor

codeskulptor.set_timeout(100)</pre></td><td><pre></pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd> </dl>

<p>
CodeSkulptor imposes a timeout on all programs, so that
long-running programs don't freeze the browser.
By default, the time limit is 5 seconds, but this allows
you to change that limit to the given number of seconds.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='file2url'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>Get CodeSkulptor URL for File</span><span class='accheadcode'><code>codeskulptor.file2url()</code></span></a></h3> <div>
<dl class="topitems">
<dt>Syntax:</dt><dd><code>codeskulptor.file2url(filename)</code></dd><dt>Example:</dt><dd><table class='ex'><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Output</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><pre class='cm'>import urllib2
import codeskulptor

a_file = urllib2.urlopen(codeskulptor.file2url('assets-Quick_fox.txt'))
print a_file.read()</pre></td><td><pre>The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy dog.</pre></td></tr></tbody></table></dd><dt>See also:</dt><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='urllib2-urlopen'><code>urllib2.urlopen</code></a> &mdash; Opening text file</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_image'><code>simplegui.load_image</code></a> &mdash; Loading image file</dd><dd><a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='load_sound'><code>simplegui.load_sound</code></a> &mdash; Loading sound file</dd> </dl>

<p>
Returns a standard CodeSkulptor URL for the given filename.
Such a URL is would be used as an argument to any
function that opens a file.
This allows you to abbreviate the URL for many files
provided by the CodeSkulptor authors.
This does not check whether the filename or URL exists.
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes CodeSkulptor Module accordion -->
</div>
</div> <!-- Closes Other Modules accordion -->
</div> <!-- Closes tabs-Other -->

<div id="tabs-CS">
<p>
<a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org' target='_blank'>CodeSkulptor</a> is a browser-based programming environment for the
programming language
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='tabs-Python'>Python</a>.
CodeSkulptor runs in
Google Chrome 18+, Mozilla Firefox 11+, and Apple Safari 6+.
Some features may work in other browsers, such as
Microsoft Internet Explorer, but do not expect
full functionality.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='CS-layout'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Window Features</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
The CodeSkulptor window consists of the following elements.
</p>

<p>
In the upper left is the control area which consists of
buttons for the main CodeSkulptor features:
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-run'>Run</a>,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-save'>Save</a>,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-download'>Download</a>,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-fresh'>Fresh URL</a>,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-local'>Open Local</a>,
and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-reset'>Reset</a>.
</p>

<p>
In the upper right are links to useful resources:
<a href="http://www.codeskulptor.org/docs.html">
the documentation you are currently reading</a>,
<a href='http://www.codeskulptor.org/demos.html' target='_blank'>example Python programs that illustrate Python
and CodeSkulptor features</a>, and
<a href='https://www.coursera.org/course/interactivepython' target='_blank'>a popular massive open online course (MOOC)</a> for which CodeSkulptor was originally created.
</p>

<p>
The left side of the main part of the page is an
editor for typing in Python programs.
Keyboard shortcuts are described below for
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='windows'>Windows</a>,
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='mac'>Mac OS</a>,
and
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='linux'>Linux</a>.
Also, if you double-click an identifier or other piece of
text, it will highlight all the matching text.
</p>

<p>
The right side of the main part of the page is the
console. When you
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-run'>run</a> the program in the editor, its printed output
and error messages are displayed here.
The console output can be
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-reset'>reset</a>.
</p>

<p>
The vertical bar between the two main parts of the window
can be adjusted to the left or right.
</p>

<div class="accordion">
<h3 id='CS-run'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Run Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-play ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Runs the Python code that is in the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-layout'>CodeSkulptor editor</a>.
Prints the results of any <code>print</code> statement
and any error messages to the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-layout'>CodeSkulptor console</a>.
If you use the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='tabs-Graphics'>SimpleGUI module</a>,
your program can create a pop-up interactive window.
</p>

<p>
To ensure that programs do not run forever and lock-up
your browser, CodeSkulptor has a time-out feature
that stops any program that runs for too long.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-save'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Save Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-disk ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Saves the contents of the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-layout'>CodeSkulptor editor</a> to &ldquo;cloud&rdquo;-based storage.
It also changes the URL shown in the browser to be
one where you can access this program again.
One way to remember this URL is to bookmark it in your
browser.
</p>

<p>
The last part of this URL is a version number &mdash;
each successive save will create a new version.
Thus, each saved version is available from its own URL.
</p>

<p>
After saving, you can
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-download'>download</a> the program to a file on your own computer.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-download'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Download Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-arrowthickstop-1-s ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Downloads a just-saved program to your own computer.
This button is only active after you have
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-save'>saved</a> this program and before you modify it further.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-fresh'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Create Fresh URL Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-suitcase ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
On each
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-save'>save</a> the URL for your program increases in version number.
This button creates a new URL independent of the
previous one.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-local'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Open Local File Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-folder-open ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Loads a Python file from your own computer into the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-layout'>CodeSkulptor editor</a>.
</p>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-reset'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Reset Button
<span class='ui-button-icon-primary ui-icon ui-icon-arrowreturnthick-1-w ui-icon-inline'></span></span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
Clears the
<a href='#' class='internal' data-dest='CS-layout'>CodeSkulptor console</a> and closes any pop-up windows created by CodeSkulptor.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id='CS-about'><a href='#'><span class='accheadtitle'>CodeSkulptor Purpose and Use</span></a></h3> <div>
<p>
CodeSkulptor was created in 2012 as a tool for teaching
Python programming, especially to beginners.
A driving goal is to be very easy to use.
Some of its main advantages for teaching are
</p>
<ul>
<li>
students do not need to install any software,
</li>
<li>
students will all have the same Python
version and the same editor, and
</li>
<li>
students can access the same programming environment and
code files from any computer.
</li>
</ul>

<p>
It was initially created for an online course,
<a href='https://www.coursera.org/course/interactivepython' target='_blank'>&ldquo;An Introduction to Interactive Programming in Python&rdquo;</a>,
by Joe Warren, Scott Rixner, John Greiner, and Stephen Wong.
It is also used in
<a href='http://www.cs.rice.edu/' target='_blank'>Computer Science courses at Rice University</a>.
</p>

<p>
Scott Rixner continues to develop CodeSkulptor,
while John Greiner develops CodeSkulptor's documentation.
</p>

</div>
</div> <!-- Closes accordion in tabs-CS -->
</div> <!-- Closes tabs-CS -->

<div id='tabs-Search'>
<p>
Searches for sections that contain <strong>all</strong>
of the following space-separated text strings.
Each string can contain letters, digits, and punctuation,
and may represent a word or a part of a word.
The search is case-insensitive.
</p>
